        }
      },
      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— CHAPTER ONE",
          "title": "Mountain Quietude",
          "byline": "BY ROBERT WILLIAM",
          "body": "Some mountains do not ask to be climbed. They ask only to be looked at, long enough to remember why we came at all. The first light catches the ridge before it reaches us, and the waiting is the point. Snow holds the shape of yesterday's wind. The stones below the summit have been arranging themselves since long before we got here, and they will continue, with some patience, after we are gone. To photograph a mountain well, you must agree to be the smaller party in the conversation, and to leave a little earlier than you wanted.",
          "vertical": "Nature",
          "folio": "p. 02"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FIELD NOTES",
          "title": "Where Rivers Begin",
          "byline": "BY MAYA HALDEN",
          "body": "There is a moment, just above the snowline, where a river decides to be a river. Before that, it is only meltwater — uncertain, scattered, unwilling. Then gravity, and a small turn of stone, and a story begins. We followed it for three days before we spoke. The trick was not to keep up. A river at altitude is older than your hurry, and it will not adjust its pace for you, and on the morning of the fourth day, when we finally caught a still pool wide enough to photograph, the picture had been waiting for us all along.",
          "vertical": "Source",
          "folio": "p. 04"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— A SLOW WALK",
          "title": "Forest Dialect",
          "byline": "BY HEN. CHAE",
          "body": "An old forest does not raise its voice. It speaks in the cracking of bark, the long sigh of pine, the low conversation of roots beneath the trail. We are tourists in the language. To listen at all, we must first stop trying to translate. Three days in, we put away the dictionary and just walked, and on the fourth day the forest finally let us photograph it without flinching. The pictures from that morning are the ones we still keep, eight years later, on the wall by the door, where the light is slowest in winter.",
          "vertical": "Forest",
          "folio": "p. 06"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FROM THE FIELDS",
          "title": "A Field of Listening",
          "byline": "BY M. OYEDEPO",
          "body": "Open country teaches different lessons than mountains do. There is nothing to hide behind. The wind moves through grass the way thought moves through a tired mind: in long, undirected waves. We sat for a whole afternoon and brought home almost nothing — three frames, none of them sharp, all of them honest. The disappointment took a few days to lift. When it did, we recognised the photographs as the truest record of an afternoon we had nearly mistaken for empty.",
          "vertical": "Field",
          "folio": "p. 08"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ASCENT",
          "title": "The Slow Climb",
          "byline": "BY S. ARDEN",
          "body": "The slow climb teaches what the summit cannot. You feel weather change in your shoulders. You learn the name of every breath. The ridge is just the place where the weather and your tiredness agree to meet, and there is no rush, because there is nowhere left to be. The pictures we made that day are not of the view. They are of the rope, the tea, the boots drying on a stone, the patient work of putting one shoulder in front of the other for nine hours. The summit appears in only one frame, out of focus, and we kept it.",
          "vertical": "Ascent",
          "folio": "p. 10"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— TWILIGHT WATERS",
          "title": "Lake at Dusk",
          "byline": "BY E. SOLBAKKEN",
          "body": "A lake at dusk holds two skies, and they argue gently about colour. The lower one is patient and a little colder; the upper one shows off. Between them, the loon calls, and the calling is the question that none of us came here to answer. We made tea on the rocks and let the camera sit unused for an hour. When we finally lifted it, the picture had already composed itself — the water was holding the sky's exit very carefully, and all we had to do was bear witness without spoiling it.",
          "vertical": "Dusk",
          "folio": "p. 12"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— UNDER THE PINES",
          "title": "Wind in the Pines",
          "byline": "BY R. KAUFMANN",
          "body": "Wind in pines does not sound like wind in anything else. It sounds older. The needles strain like rigging on a ship that has been at sea too long. We make our coffee in the lee of a rock and let the music go on without us, and that is the closest we have come to peace this year. The light reaches us in pieces, sieved through a million green needles, and never the same way twice in a single hour. The photographs we keep from these mornings are mostly of the ground.",
          "vertical": "Pines",
          "folio": "p. 14"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ICE AND TIME",
          "title": "Glacial Memory",
          "byline": "BY I. BJÖRK",
          "body": "A glacier is the slowest argument the world makes. It moves at the speed of forgetting. Standing at its terminus, we are merely the latest in a line of small, warm visitors. The ice does not notice us. The ice has other matters in mind, and they are measured in centuries, not in afternoons. We tried, that summer, to photograph it without nostalgia. It was harder than it sounds. A glacier on film carries its own retreat with it, and the picture, no matter how careful, is already a small elegy.",
          "vertical": "Ice",
          "folio": "p. 16"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LONG COAST",
          "title": "A Long Coast",
          "byline": "BY F. AALTONEN",
          "body": "The coast does not need an audience. The waves perform whether or not anyone is watching, and they have been doing this for considerably longer than anyone has been keeping count. We came in November when the wind was loud enough to interrupt our own thoughts, which was a relief that year. The light is hard on a long coast in late autumn. The horizon is, as a rule, the only generous element. We photographed the same hundred metres of beach for six days, and on the seventh we agreed that we had finished, and we drove home.",
          "vertical": "Coast",
          "folio": "p. 18"
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LONG RETURN",
          "title": "The Quiet Years",
          "byline": "BY T. MATSURA",
          "body": "We came back to the valley after seven years. Almost nothing had moved, except us. The same fence was leaning at the same patient angle. The same heron stood, or one that had taken its place, and looked through us as it always had, with the polite indifference of country places. The pictures from that week are quieter than the ones we took the first time. We had less to prove. The valley had been waiting in much the same posture, and it accepted our return without comment, which is the kindest thing a place can do.",
          "vertical": "Years",
          "folio": "p. 20"
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
