      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 01",
          "title": "A Quiet Light",
          "number": "02",
          "byline": "BY ROBERT WILLIAM",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "A Quiet Light is a study of the hours before the world is fully awake. The series was photographed over four months in a single coastal town, in available daylight, on medium format film. The intent was not to document, but to slow the looking — to give the morning the attention it usually goes without. Eighteen photographs were selected from a working set of more than four hundred frames. The book is sequenced by hour rather than location, beginning with five-thirty and ending shortly before noon."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 02",
          "title": "Surface",
          "number": "03",
          "byline": "BY MAYA HALDEN",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "body": "Surface is a portfolio of close-range studies: stone, water, paper, skin. The aim was to remove the easy compositional crutches — horizon, subject, narrative — and to ask whether a single texture could carry an image on its own. Some of the answers surprised us. Others, of course, did not. The series was photographed in a single studio over a calendar year, under a north-facing window, with no artificial light and no second exposure. Forty plates were edited from the working archive."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 03",
          "title": "Drift",
          "number": "04",
          "byline": "BY S. ARDEN",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "Drift was photographed from a small wooden boat on a river that had no particular hurry. Twelve days, a single roll of film per day, no rule against repetition. The work that emerged is concerned less with the river itself than with the way attention behaves when there is, for once, very little for it to latch onto. The final selection of eighteen frames is sequenced by day rather than by composition. The boat does not appear, but its slight rocking is, on close looking, in nearly all of them."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 04",
          "title": "Hour Blue",
          "number": "05",
          "byline": "BY E. SOLBAKKEN",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "body": "Hour Blue is the result of a year-long appointment with one moment. Every night, twenty minutes after sunset, a single frame from a single window. The resulting series is a quiet argument about how much, and how little, a city changes from one evening to the next. The work was made without flash, without retouching, and without skipping a single date. Three hundred and sixty-five negatives form the working archive. Twelve final plates were chosen for the printed edition, one for each month of the year."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 05",
          "title": "Salt and Iron",
          "number": "06",
          "byline": "BY T. MATSURA",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "Salt and Iron is a documentary study of a small commercial harbour at the bookends of its working day. Photographed in the half-hour before sunrise and the half-hour after sunset, the work tries to honour the harbour's mechanics without dressing them up in the usual romance of working light. The series was made over a full season, from late March to early November. Twenty-two plates were selected for the final edit, and a small companion volume of contact sheets accompanies the printed edition."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 06",
          "title": "Slow Glass",
          "number": "07",
          "byline": "BY P. ROSEN",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "body": "Slow Glass is a series of very long exposures, made through old window panes in derelict houses. The film records, over the course of an hour, what the glass has been looking at: the shifting weather outside, the slow wandering of dust, the occasional shadow of a passer-by who never stops to look back. Nine plates form the final edit. Each was exposed for between forty and seventy-two minutes on a tripod that had to be kept exactly still — a discipline that turned out to be the harder of the project's two crafts."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 07",
          "title": "Untitled (Garden)",
          "number": "08",
          "byline": "BY M. OYEDEPO",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "Untitled (Garden) is a long, deliberately uneventful project. One small garden, photographed weekly, for two years. There is no event the work is leading up to. The interest is in the slow accumulation of changes that none of us, individually, would have thought worth photographing. The thirty-week and seventy-three-week frames sit beside each other in the final layout, and the differences between them are easy to miss on a first look — which is, in the end, the entire point of the project."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 08",
          "title": "North Light",
          "number": "09",
          "byline": "BY J. AKINOLA",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "North Light is a portrait series produced entirely under a single, unmoving studio window. No reflectors, no fill, no theatre. The sitters arrive, the window does its slow work, and we leave the room when the light leaves it. The constraint, eventually, becomes the picture's main material. Sixteen sitters were photographed over the course of a single spring, each in a single visit of approximately fifty minutes. The book is sequenced by date, and the light recedes by a small visible margin between the first and last plates."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 09",
          "title": "Architecture of Air",
          "number": "10",
          "byline": "BY V. ATALA",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "Architecture of Air is concerned with the rooms of a building, photographed in their unoccupied state. The work proposes that every well-designed room has, in addition to walls and floors, a particular shape of air — and that this shape can, with a little patience and the right hour, be photographed. Fourteen plates were made over a single summer in three buildings, all completed within the last fifteen years. The book is laid out room by room, and the absence of figures is consistent and intentional throughout the entire edit."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 10",
          "title": "Last Hour",
          "number": "11",
          "byline": "BY ALL CONTRIBUTORS",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "Last Hour collects work made in the closing sixty minutes of an ordinary day, by ten contributors across four cities. There is no theme beyond that constraint. What links the pictures is a particular tiredness in the light, and the way people behave when they have stopped trying to be photographed. The book is laid out in the chronological order in which the photographs were submitted, rather than by contributor. A short text accompanies each frame, written by the photographer in the week the picture was taken."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
