          "inCard": true
        },
        {
          "type": "body",
          "x": 6,
          "y": 76,
          "w": 30,
          "h": 12,
          "align": "left",
          "size": "xs",
          "weight": "regular",
          "lineHeight": "relaxed",
          "inCard": true
        },
        {
          "type": "folio",
          "x": 90,
          "y": 94,
          "w": 8,
          "h": 3,
          "align": "right",
          "size": "xs",
          "weight": "regular",
          "overlay": true,
          "color": "muted"
        }
      ],
      "decorations": [
        {
          "type": "box",
          "x": 4,
          "y": 58,
          "w": 34,
          "h": 34,
          "color": "rgba(20,20,20,0.85)",
          "border": null
        },
        {
          "type": "line",
          "orientation": "horizontal",
          "x1": 6,
          "y1": 66,
          "x2": 14,
          "y2": 66,
          "thickness": 1,
          "color": "accent"
        }
      ],
      "char_limits": {
        "eyebrow": {
          "min": 13,
          "ideal": 33,
          "max": 39,
          "lines": 1,
          "case": "uppercase"
        },
        "title": {
          "min": 11,
          "ideal": 22,
          "max": 29,
          "lines": 2,
          "case": "title"
        },
        "body": {
          "min": 181,
          "ideal": 330,
          "max": 461,
          "lines": 10,
          "case": "sentence"
        },
        "folio": {
          "min": 1,
          "ideal": 4,
          "max": 8,
          "lines": 1,
          "case": "lowercase"
        }
      },
      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— WILD SUBJECTS",
          "title": "Animal Instinct",
          "folio": "p. 14",
          "body": "The animal does not owe you a picture. You sit in your hide for nine hours, and on the tenth, if you have been quiet enough, the world allows you a glimpse. The frame you bring back is half luck and half listening, and you cannot reliably tell which half is which."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— THE LONG WATCH",
          "title": "The Watching Hour",
          "folio": "p. 22",
          "body": "There is an hour in every shoot when the photographer becomes a piece of furniture. The room continues without you. People rest their faces. The light, no longer performed for, returns to itself. The picture, when it arrives, arrives without warning."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— CINEMATIC",
          "title": "Cinema in Stillness",
          "folio": "p. 30",
          "body": "The best stills carry a feeling of motion left behind. Someone has just spoken; the air has not yet caught up. We see the room before the next thing happens. The frame holds an aftermath and a threshold at once, and the viewer does the rest."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LIGHT STUDY",
          "title": "Light Made Slow",
          "folio": "p. 38",
          "body": "Slow light is the photographer's true material. At six in the evening, the world develops itself: shadows lengthen and become specific, surfaces remember they are made of texture. We do not invent the picture. We arrive in time to recognise it before the hour passes."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SMOKE & SILENCE",
          "title": "Smoke and Silence",
          "folio": "p. 46",
          "body": "Smoke turns a room into a picture. It softens edges, slows down the air, gives the light something to hold onto. The silence does the rest. You do not direct it; you wait until the room has emptied of everything except the smoke, and then you photograph what is left."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— EMPTY ROOMS",
          "title": "Empty Rooms",
          "folio": "p. 54",
          "body": "An empty room is more honest than a full one. Without people, it shows you what it actually is: the angle of a chair, the dust on the sill, the way the light has been moving across the floor for years. The room knows things its occupants will not photograph themselves."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— AFTER HOURS",
          "title": "After Hours",
          "folio": "p. 62",
          "body": "After hours, the city becomes the photograph it has been pretending all day not to be. The neon does its long, tired work. The street is wet for no reason. Someone closes a door across the way, and you press the shutter without thinking, and that frame turns out to be the one you keep."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LONG SHADOWS",
          "title": "Long Shadows",
          "folio": "p. 70",
          "body": "By six in the evening, every object is dragging a longer version of itself across the ground. The shadows are doing the heavier work in every frame. We follow them, instead of their owners. The pictures end up being about the time of day rather than its protagonists, and that is a fair record."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LAST FRAME",
          "title": "Last Frame",
          "folio": "p. 78",
          "body": "The last frame on a roll is rarely the best one. But it is, almost always, the most honest. By the time you reach it, you have stopped trying to be a photographer. You are merely a person with a camera, very tired, looking at one more thing before you go home."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— NEGATIVE SPACE",
          "title": "Negative Space",
          "folio": "p. 86",
          "body": "We were taught to look at the subject. The harder lesson came later: look at what surrounds it, and notice that the surroundings do most of the work. Empty walls, white sky, the room's own breath. A subject without space around it is only an announcement."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
