      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 01",
          "title": "Postcards from Lisbon",
          "kicker": "A week of getting properly lost. Yellow trams, blue tiles, very slow afternoons.",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "Lisbon is a city that will not be hurried. The hills tire you out before lunch. The tiles repeat themselves with small variations, like a piece of music. By the third afternoon you stop asking where you are going, which is when the city, having been polite about it, finally agrees to show you something. We had rented a small apartment in Alfama with a balcony just wide enough for two chairs and an ashtray, and we spent more evenings on it than we had planned. The trams went past at the same hour each night. The neighbours sang from one balcony to another, in a manner we could not have explained at home. None of it was for our benefit, which was, of course, the point. We came back with three rolls of film, a notebook of half-translated phrases, and a slight tan from afternoons that we would have been embarrassed to call useful but cannot now imagine without."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 02",
          "title": "Morning in Kyoto",
          "kicker": "Five days, three temples, no plan. How a city wakes when it has been awake for centuries.",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "In Kyoto, morning is not an event but a practice. By six, the temple gates are sweeping themselves; by seven, the steam from the first noodle stalls is already a kind of architecture. Walk slowly enough and the city will let you in on its smaller routines, the ones it does not put in the brochures. We stayed in a guesthouse in Higashiyama, ten minutes' walk from a temple whose name we never learned to pronounce correctly. The bell rang every morning at quarter past six, and we got up because there seemed no excuse not to. The first hour of the day in Kyoto is, in our experience, the best hour. By eight, the buses arrive. By nine, the city has put on the face it shows to its visitors, and you must remember the seven o'clock version yourself. We took fewer photographs than we expected, and remembered more. The two are, perhaps, related."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 03",
          "title": "A Week in Provence",
          "kicker": "Long lunches and a great deal of sun. On doing almost nothing, well.",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "Provence is engineered for slowness. The lavender does its work without you. Lunch begins at one and ends, vaguely, somewhere near four. We rented a stone house with a single bad lamp and stayed a week, and the only thing we wrote in our notebooks was the colour of the hills at six. The market in Sault opens on Wednesdays. The bakery, on most days, runs out of the rosemary loaf by eleven. The pool was warmer in the morning than in the evening, which is the opposite of what we expected and a fact we still cannot account for. We saw a single hare on the road one night, paused in the headlights, then gone. The hare did not appear in any of the photographs, and we did not bother to mention it to anyone after we got home, but I remember it more clearly than the village. That is what Provence does."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 04",
          "title": "Below the Eiffel",
          "kicker": "On finding new angles on old things. A very famous tower, photographed from underneath.",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "Famous monuments resist photography by being already photographed. The trick is to refuse the postcard. Stand underneath. Get closer than is comfortable. Look up until your neck disagrees. Even an over-photographed tower has a private life, and most of it happens at the level of the rivets. We spent four evenings under it. The first two were tourists' work, and the photographs from those nights are competent and forgettable. The third evening it rained, and we stayed under the tower as a kind of shelter, and the picture I still keep from that trip was made in that hour. The fourth evening was for confirmation, which is the photographer's least romantic work but his most honest. The tower itself has been photographed by everyone who has ever stood beneath it. The photograph you eventually keep is the one no one else thought to make at exactly that hour."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 05",
          "title": "The Atlantic Coast",
          "kicker": "Seven days, four lighthouses, far too much wind. On loving bad weather.",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "A lighthouse coast is best in weather no one else wants. Drive out in November. Bring an old coat. The light will not pose for you, but it will eventually agree to be photographed, briefly, between squalls. Keep going. The fifth lighthouse is always the best one, and you will not have planned for it. We stayed in small inns. The wind, on most nights, was loud enough to keep us up; on a couple of nights, loud enough to make conversation pointless, which turned out to be a kind of holiday in itself. The pictures from that week are, on average, the most honest of anything we made that year. They are also the most uncomfortable to look at, because the cold is in them, and the disappointment of failed exposures, and the small triumphs of hot soup at six in the evening. I would do it again."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 06",
          "title": "A Month in Liguria",
          "kicker": "Five villages, one trail, several thousand stairs. On vertical Italy.",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "body": "Cinque Terre was built by people with strong legs and excellent taste. The trail between the five towns is mostly stairs, occasionally vineyards, and now and then an unscheduled view of the sea that asks you to forget what you came up here for. The thigh ache is the price of admission. We stayed in Vernazza for a month, far longer than was reasonable, and ate from the same three restaurants in rotation until we learned the proprietors' children's names. The trail, by the second week, had become a daily affair rather than a destination. We knew where the hard parts were. We had favourite turns. The sea, more than the towns, was the thing we kept photographing — the way it changes under wind, under cloud, under the long Italian afternoon. The pictures we kept are, in retrospect, almost all of water, though we spent most of our time on stone."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 07",
          "title": "Old Streets, New Sun",
          "kicker": "On towns that have been broken and put back. A rebuilt city, rehearsing itself.",
          "folio": "p. 52",
          "body": "Dresden was rebuilt one stone at a time. Walking through it now, you can almost feel the city remembering, deciding which of its details to keep and which to soften. The sun is honest about it. Light falls equally on the old stones and the new; only the patina, eventually, will tell them apart. We had three days, which is too short to know a city, and we spent the first one walking without a plan, which is, in our experience, the only way to learn one's way around. The Frauenkirche square in the early morning is empty in a particular Eastern European way — the chairs out, the awnings still rolled, no music yet. We made our best photographs in those hours. By eleven, the city has assembled itself for visitors. By eleven, you must have already finished the day's working photographs and be ready for coffee."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 08",
          "title": "An Evening in Rome",
          "kicker": "On the art of taking up a chair. How to spend an evening in two euros and an espresso.",
          "folio": "p. 60",
          "body": "Rome rewards patience the way other cities reward wallets. Find a café in Trastevere with a slightly grumpy proprietor. Order one espresso, slowly. Stay until the light has changed three times. The bill will be small, the chair will be uncomfortable, and the evening will be one of the best you have on this trip. We did this for six nights running. The proprietor began, by the fourth night, to bring water without being asked. By the fifth, he sat down, briefly, and complained about the weather, which was a sign of acceptance more meaningful than any tourist guide will tell you about. We took only one photograph in that café, on the last evening, and it is the one we kept. The other six nights are remembered without pictures, which is, in the end, the way most evenings should be remembered."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 09",
          "title": "The Long Train North",
          "kicker": "Twelve hours, three books, one window. On loving overnight trains.",
          "folio": "p. 68",
          "body": "An overnight train is the best invention humanity has on offer. The window does the work of an entire holiday. Birch forests slide past for hours; the dining car is melancholy in the right way; you sleep poorly and wake somewhere your body has not yet agreed to be, which is the whole point. We took the sleeper from Helsinki north, in February, and the dark outside the window was so complete that we mostly read. By morning we were in Lapland, and the snow was higher than the train had any right to be passing. We did not photograph any of this — the light was too low, the windows too smeared, the rocking too constant. The pictures from that trip are all from after we got off. The train itself remains in memory only, which is, perhaps, where it ought to."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— DISPATCH 10",
          "title": "Where the Map Ends",
          "kicker": "On going one stop further. Borders, edges, and the towns no one books in advance.",
          "folio": "p. 76",
          "body": "The interesting work of travel begins where the map gets vague. One station past the recommended stop. The town no guidebook praises. The locals are not putting on a show because no one is watching, and the espresso is somehow cheaper, and a different kind of evening becomes possible. We got off, that summer, at a station whose name we cannot now remember, and walked half a kilometre to a small hotel that had been recommended by a friend of a friend. The bar served a single brand of beer. The kitchen closed at nine. The owner's son was building a kayak in the courtyard, and the radio played nothing we recognised. We stayed two nights, and the photographs we made are not particularly good, but the evenings are remembered with unreasonable warmth. The map, that week, was a hindrance more than a help."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
