      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ALMOST REMEMBERED",
          "script": "Summer Half-Recalled",
          "kicker": "An essay on the unreliable archive — Polaroids of a half-recalled season.",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · ONE",
          "body": "Most of the summer is gone now. Not lost — gone, which is different. The photographs we took are softer than the days were. The ones we did not take have done what they were always going to do, and slipped, by inches, into a kind of warm fog. The fog turns out to be the better record. There was an afternoon in early August, somewhere outside the village, when we lay in the grass for what cannot have been more than an hour. I remember the grass exactly. I cannot tell you who was there. I cannot tell you what we said. The grass, however, has stayed: dry, slightly bent, full of insects."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— UNSENT",
          "script": "A Letter Unsent",
          "kicker": "Things we wrote, then thought better of, then kept. On drawers, second thoughts.",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · TWO",
          "body": "Every honest desk has a drawer that is, in fact, an archive of second thoughts. Letters never sent. Sentences crossed out and not replaced. The drawer remembers more accurately than the diary does, because the drawer was not trying. The pictures from that summer are filed there, under a different name. I wrote a letter, in the August of that year, to someone I had not seen in eleven years and would not see again. I did not send it. I read it again the following winter, and most of it embarrassed me, but two lines did not, and I copied them into a notebook I still carry."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— A QUIET YEAR",
          "script": "Unpictured Year",
          "kicker": "On living off-camera. What an unphotographed year remembers about itself.",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · THREE",
          "body": "There was a year when I did not make a single photograph. By the end of it, I expected to find a hole in my memory; instead, I found the year had stored itself elsewhere — in smells, in songs that had been on the radio, in two or three conversations I could repeat verbatim. The body, it turns out, has its own archive. The kitchen of the apartment we rented, that year, comes back to me whenever I peel garlic. The hallway smelled of tobacco that did not belong to us. There was a draught at the door that made the curtain swing in a particular way at four in the afternoon."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LATE LIGHT",
          "script": "Dust Light",
          "kicker": "On rooms remembered for the air in them. An afternoon, an empty room, slow gold.",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · FOUR",
          "body": "Some rooms we remember not for what was in them, but for the light that was. A hallway in late afternoon, dust suspended in a single bar of gold, no one home. The room was unimportant. The light was the entire occasion. Years later, I can still walk through it in my head, and I almost never get the colour wrong. The house is sold now. The new owners, when I drove past last summer, had repainted the front door, and through the window I could see that they had moved the bookshelf to the other wall. The hallway, with the four o'clock light in it, is the part that I have kept."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— THE OLD HOUSE",
          "script": "Garden Notes",
          "kicker": "Notes from a house that no longer exists. Tomatoes, cats, a bay-leaf kitchen.",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · FIVE",
          "body": "The house has been sold for a long time now, but the garden is still there in the inventory of my body. The tomatoes are exactly where they were. The cats wander past in the same order. The kitchen, in particular, is so well preserved in memory that I can find the salt without looking. None of this is in the photographs. The photographs from those summers are mostly of people, who have changed, who have aged, who have, in some cases, moved on entirely. The garden, by some quiet act of self-defence, is the part of those summers that did not change."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— EVIDENCE",
          "script": "Tickets in Drawers",
          "kicker": "On small archives. Stubs, receipts, evidence of having been somewhere.",
          "folio": "p. 48",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · SIX",
          "body": "I never throw out tickets. The drawer where I keep them is the closest thing in my flat to a working archive. A train stub from a town I cannot remember the name of. A cinema ticket for a film I did not finish. Each one is a small, accidentally honest record of a day I would otherwise have forgotten entirely. The drawer is in the second-from-bottom of the desk by the window. I do not open it more than once or twice a year. When I do, I take an hour, and I read them in chronological order whenever I let myself."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— A SLOW MONTH",
          "script": "Slow July",
          "kicker": "On uneventful summers — the year nothing happened, and we remembered everything.",
          "folio": "p. 56",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · SEVEN",
          "body": "It was the slowest July any of us could remember. Nothing happened, in the literal sense. We sat on porches. We read the same paperback in shifts. The cousin from the city stopped trying to make plans, and discovered, to her surprise, that she had become quite fond of doing nothing. We talk about that month more than any other. The conversations we had, sitting on the porch in the evenings, are easier to recall than most things from that year, perhaps because there was so little else competing with them. None of these are good photographs. All of them are, in some private way, exactly the right kind of summer."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FOUND",
          "script": "Strangers Album",
          "kicker": "An album bought at a flea market, owner unknown. On lives we did not live.",
          "folio": "p. 64",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · EIGHT",
          "body": "I bought the album for two euros. The strangers in it have been someone else's family for sixty years. They are unaware of me. I cannot return them to themselves. So I keep the album on a shelf and look at them sometimes, with the polite, unanswerable curiosity that one tends to feel for people who cannot, any longer, be introduced. The first photograph is dated 1962, on the back, in a careful hand. The last is from 1979. There is a small dog in many of them, and a woman with a very specific haircut who appears in a third of the photographs."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— LOUD YEARS",
          "script": "When Rooms Were Loud",
          "kicker": "On the volume of certain years. Before the children grew up, before the dog aged.",
          "folio": "p. 72",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · NINE",
          "body": "The house was loud for about fourteen years. We did not notice at the time, because there was nothing to compare it to. Now the rooms make a particular shape of silence. The dog, mostly asleep, takes up about a quarter of the kitchen. We talk to each other over the noise of nothing, and we are surprisingly good at it. The kitchen, in particular, is the room that has changed the most. There used to be three radios going at once, on three different stations, none of them ours. The walls are the same walls. Only the volume is different."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SECOND HOLDING",
          "script": "Things Held Twice",
          "kicker": "On returning to small things — objects we have picked up at two different ages.",
          "folio": "p. 80",
          "runninghead": "ALMOST REMEMBERED · TEN",
          "body": "Some objects make their way back to us. A book read at twelve and at thirty-six. A coat that has been moved between four different cities and is finally just an old coat. The second holding is the interesting one. The object has not changed; we have, in small private ways, and the pictures we make of it are different. The paperback I am thinking of has been re-read four times now. The cover is held on with tape. The margins, in three different handwritings, are full of comments, most of which I do not entirely agree with anymore. None of these objects are worth photographing, individually."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
