      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 12 PAGES · NATURE",
          "title": "On the Slow Climb",
          "kicker": "There is no hurry in the high places.",
          "caption": "Final pitch at 4,120 metres, the morning after the storm cleared.",
          "byline": "BY ROBERT WILLIAM",
          "folio": "p. 14",
          "body": "There is no hurry in the high places. The slow climb teaches what the summit cannot. You feel weather change in your shoulders. You learn the name of every breath. The ridge is just the place where the weather and your tiredness agree to meet, and there is no rush, because there is nowhere left to be. We came to the mountains for the wrong reasons that summer. There were arguments at home that the trip was meant to interrupt. There was a job that one of us was thinking about leaving and the other was thinking about taking. We had brought, between us, four cameras, two old paperbacks neither of us would finish, and a kind of unspoken agreement to let the country make the decisions for us for a week. The first day we walked too far. The second day we walked further. The third day we stopped, because the weather had stopped on our behalf, and sat under a small overhang with the rain coming sideways, and made tea on a stove that was at least twenty years older than either of us. The pictures we made that week are not of the view. They are of the rope, the tea, the boots drying on a stone, the patient work of putting one shoulder in front of the other for nine hours."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 14 PAGES · OCEAN",
          "title": "The Wild Coast",
          "kicker": "On loving weather no one else wants.",
          "caption": "Cape Race, the morning after the second storm cleared.",
          "byline": "BY E. SOLBAKKEN",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "On loving weather no one else wants. A lighthouse coast is best in November, when the tourists have gone and the wind has remembered itself. Drive out late. Bring an old coat. The light will not pose for you, but it will eventually agree to be photographed, briefly, between squalls. Keep going. The fifth lighthouse is always the best one, and you will not have planned for it. We took that drive in a year that had been long. There were things at home that the country could not solve, and we knew it, but the country did not seem to mind being asked. The first night we stayed in a small inn whose owner, when we asked about the weather, said only that the weather had been like this for fifty years and would continue to be. He said this with a slight pride. The fish that night was very good. The wine was honest, and there was only one kind. We slept poorly because of the wind, and woke at five because of the gulls, and the photographs from that week are, on average, the most honest of anything we made that year. They are also the most uncomfortable to look at, because the cold is in them, and the small triumphs of hot soup at six in the evening."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 10 PAGES · WILDERNESS",
          "title": "The Mountain Years",
          "kicker": "On going back to a place that did not need us.",
          "caption": "South pasture, seven Septembers after the first photograph.",
          "byline": "BY T. MATSURA",
          "folio": "p. 42",
          "body": "On going back to a place that did not need us. We came back to the valley after seven years. Almost nothing had moved, except us. The same fence was leaning at the same patient angle. The same heron stood, or one that had taken its place, and looked through us as it always had, with the polite indifference of country places. The valley does not, of course, recognise us. It does not remember the summer we spent there in our twenties, when we were broker than we knew and happier than we deserved to be. It does not remember the winter we drove through in a car that was about to break, on a road that was barely a road. The pictures from that week are quieter than the ones we took the first time. We had less to prove. The valley had been waiting in much the same posture, and it accepted our return without comment, which is the kindest thing a place can do. The light had not changed. The smells had not changed. Only we had changed, and the pictures show it, in ways that are not flattering and not unwelcome."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 12 PAGES · WATER",
          "title": "Quiet Sea",
          "kicker": "An afternoon, mostly silent, on a coast we will not name.",
          "caption": "Quay, end of the season, eleven Septembers in a row.",
          "byline": "BY S. ARDEN",
          "folio": "p. 56",
          "body": "An afternoon, mostly silent, on a coast we will not name. There are coasts you visit, and there are coasts you go back to. This one we have gone back to, every September, for eleven years. The town is small, and not particularly photogenic, which is a large part of why we keep going. The bakery opens at six. The harbour has, on most mornings, four boats and a man who appears not to own any of them. The pictures we make there have not changed substantially in a decade. We have given up trying. The light is the light, the boats are the boats, the man who does not own them is, depending on the year, slightly older. There is a small bench at the end of the quay, and we have sat on it for the better part of an afternoon every year that we have come, and it is the only place in the world where I am reliably bored in a way that I find restful. The boredom, in fact, may be the entire point of the trip. We do not photograph the bench. The bench, we have decided, is not for photography."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 16 PAGES · TRAVEL",
          "title": "Open Country",
          "kicker": "What the empty parts of the map remember.",
          "caption": "Roadside, west of the last town with a petrol pump.",
          "byline": "BY P. ROSEN",
          "folio": "p. 70",
          "body": "What the empty parts of the map remember. We drove west that month, and kept driving until the radio gave up. There was a stretch of three afternoons during which we saw, between us, perhaps a dozen other cars. The towns were spaced an hour apart, and most of them had a single petrol pump, and a single café whose sign promised pie. We made it a rule, briefly, to stop in every café whose sign promised pie. The rule was abandoned by the second day, on the grounds that the pies were not, on balance, very good, and that the company at the counter was, in most cases, the more interesting find. We made friends with two truck drivers in two different states. One of them gave us a road we had not heard of. The other gave us, without realising it, the picture from that trip that we kept, and that we hung in the kitchen, and that has, every year since, made me want to drive west again. We have not done it. We probably will not. The picture is the version we kept, and that is the one I look at while I do the dishes."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 14 PAGES · WINTER",
          "title": "The Long Ridge",
          "kicker": "Notes from a high pass, in weather that did not belong to us.",
          "caption": "High pass, the third morning, after thirty hours of storm.",
          "byline": "BY R. KAUFMANN",
          "folio": "p. 84",
          "body": "Notes from a high pass, in weather that did not belong to us. The pass is at four thousand metres. The weather, when we were there, was several centuries older than we were, and behaved accordingly. We had two days to make the crossing, and we made it in three, because the second day's storm came earlier than expected and pinned us in the second hut for thirty hours. The hut had a kettle, and a roof that did not entirely work, and a small library of books in three languages, none of which were ours. We read the labels on the tinned food, mostly. We slept in our coats. The wind, on the second night, was loud enough that we had to nod at one another instead of speaking. The picture I kept from that crossing was made on the morning of the third day, when the storm cleared and the light was so flat and white that everything in the frame, including us, was a single grey value. It is not a beautiful picture. It is, however, an accurate one, and that is, in retrospect, what I had hoped for from the trip."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 12 PAGES · FOREST",
          "title": "The Northwoods",
          "kicker": "On forests that do not raise their voices.",
          "caption": "Beech grove, mid-October, after the rain that did not come.",
          "byline": "BY HEN. CHAE",
          "folio": "p. 98",
          "body": "On forests that do not raise their voices. An old forest does not announce itself. It speaks in the cracking of bark, the long sigh of pine, the low conversation of roots beneath the trail. We are tourists in the language. To listen at all, we must first stop trying to translate. We spent twelve days in the northwoods that autumn. The cabin we rented had, in addition to a small wood stove, a single window that faced east, and we made it our habit to sit at it at first light and drink coffee in silence. There was little wildlife to speak of, that year — a single fox, a number of jays, the occasional unidentifiable noise after dark. The pictures we kept are not of any of these. They are of the forest itself, which was the entire occasion. We had brought a notebook and used almost none of it. We had brought four rolls of film and used three. There was no plan, which was, in the end, the right approach to a forest that did not seem to require one."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 10 PAGES · LOWLAND",
          "title": "A Long Valley",
          "kicker": "The country between two ranges, in late summer.",
          "caption": "Roadside paddock, the third town, the fifth afternoon.",
          "byline": "BY M. OYEDEPO",
          "folio": "p. 112",
          "body": "The country between two ranges, in late summer. There is a kind of valley that is too long to be a valley and too narrow to be a plain, and the light in such a valley behaves in a way that is particular to itself. We spent a week in one of them in August. The road runs the length of the valley, and there is a small town every twenty kilometres, and we slept in a different one every night. We were not, by then, on holiday in any honest sense. We had been driving for ten days. The car had a small problem with the steering that the third mechanic, in the third town, finally fixed. We had agreed, by the second town, to stop trying to photograph the journey and to photograph only what stopped us. The pictures that came out of that week are, in retrospect, the most honest record of any of our long trips. They are mostly of small things — a kettle on a counter, a chair on a porch, a horse in a paddock — and they are, when laid out together, more like a single conversation than the usual portfolio of separate impressions."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 14 PAGES · LAKES",
          "title": "Glass Lakes",
          "kicker": "Twelve mornings, two lakes, one tripod.",
          "caption": "Eighth morning, north lake, before the wind came up.",
          "byline": "BY I. BJÖRK",
          "folio": "p. 126",
          "body": "Twelve mornings, two lakes, one tripod. The lakes are forty kilometres apart, and the road between them is mostly birch. We drove one to the other and back again every other morning for two weeks, and made the same picture, more or less, each time. The work was deliberately repetitive. The interest was in what changed between the days, which was, on most mornings, very little. Twice the lakes were entirely flat, and the photographs were, on those mornings, almost identical despite the forty-kilometre distance between them. Twice there was wind. Once it rained, and we made no photograph at all, and drove home, and watched a film, and went to bed early. The picture I kept is from the eighth morning, which was unremarkable in every recordable respect, and which I cannot, when I look at the picture now, distinguish in memory from any of the others. The picture itself is of one of the lakes — I am no longer certain which — at the hour we always arrived, with the same trees on the far shore."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "FEATURE · ESSAY · 12 PAGES · CLOSING",
          "title": "Last Light",
          "kicker": "On the year's final hour, photographed deliberately.",
          "caption": "Thirty-first afternoon, north window, four-fifteen, year's end.",
          "byline": "BY V. ATALA",
          "folio": "p. 140",
          "body": "On the year's final hour, photographed deliberately. The last hour of light in any given year is, of course, an arbitrary thing — it depends on where you are, on the weather, on whether you are paying attention. We spent the December of that year, the whole month, paying attention to it. Every afternoon, regardless of weather or commitment, we went out at four and stood somewhere for an hour and watched the light leave. We made photographs on most days. We made better photographs on perhaps a third of them. By the end of the month, we had a working archive of thirty-one frames, sequenced by date, and we put them on the wall in chronological order in the kitchen. The progression is, when you stand back, unremarkable. The light leaves a little earlier each evening. The colour shifts, by inches. The differences between consecutive days are mostly invisible. The differences between the first frame and the last, however, are unmistakable, and the project, by accident, became the year's clearest single record."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
