      },
      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "vertical": "Twin",
          "eyebrow": "— A PAIR OF PEAKS",
          "title": "Two Mountains",
          "caption": "East and west summits, the same valley, photographed forty minutes apart at the year's last light.",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "There were two mountains in the valley, and we never could agree on which we preferred. One was the more obvious choice — symmetrical, snow-topped, photogenic. The other was a less polite shape, scrubbed at by weather, half its summit knocked off in some forgotten century. The disagreement, sustained over fifteen summers, became a small private joke. We would arrive in the village, drop our bags, and walk to the meadow at the edge of town to have it again. The light fell on the two mountains differently, depending on the hour and the year. By evening, the more obvious one was already in shade, and the rougher one had taken on the kind of last gold that only a certain weather grants."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Both",
          "eyebrow": "— RIVER & SEA",
          "title": "Where Both Are Water",
          "caption": "Estuary mouth in October, fresh water and salt water folded into one unstable surface.",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "The river is forty years old by the time it reaches the sea, and it does not seem to want to arrive. There is a flat grey kilometre at the estuary where the two waters argue politely about salinity, then give up and become each other. We stood at the mouth for an hour at low tide. The wind came off the sea and the rain came off the land and we, by accident, stood exactly between them. The two waters are not the same colour. They are not even, in any honest sense, the same substance. Where they meet, the line is visible for perhaps a hundred metres, and then it surrenders, and there is only the larger water, which has, by inheritance, swallowed the smaller."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Edge",
          "eyebrow": "— FOREST & FIELD",
          "title": "Where the Trees End",
          "caption": "Northern edge of the spruce wood, last birch of the season, looking south into open pasture.",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "The forest gives way to the field with a clear opinion. There is no apologetic interval — the trees end, the grass begins, and the boundary is so exact that you can stand on it with one foot in each kingdom. We walked the edge for three days, photographing both sides of it. The forest was reluctant to give up its small dramas; the field, by contrast, had nothing to hide. The two photographs we kept are face-to-face on the wall in the kitchen. The forest one is dark and full of small noises. The field one is mostly weather. Neither is improved by being looked at without the other; together, they make a single argument about how thin a line a habit of vegetation can be."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Pair",
          "eyebrow": "— LAKE & SKY",
          "title": "The Two Mirrors",
          "caption": "Mountain tarn at first light, and again at last light, the same hour separated by an entire day.",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "body": "A tarn at altitude is the most reliable mirror nature provides. We came to one twice in a single day — at five in the morning and at nine in the evening — and made the same photograph at both ends. The two negatives are nearly identical. Only the colour temperature gives the lie. The morning lake is pewter; the evening lake is bronze. The mountain on the far shore is the same mountain. The clouds, as it happened, had not appreciably changed. We sat between the two exposures, in the middle of the day, and read paperbacks under a tree, and discussed almost nothing. The two pictures, when we hung them, were inseparable."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Two",
          "eyebrow": "— STONE & SAND",
          "title": "Two Ways of Being Slow",
          "caption": "Granite shoreline above, dune crest below, the same coast on the same morning, four kilometres apart.",
          "folio": "p. 48",
          "body": "Stone is a thousand years older than sand, but you would not know it to look at them on the same beach. The granite at the headland was cooled in some early geology and has been rounding itself, with great patience, ever since. The sand a kilometre south is the granite's much-younger child, ground down by water that has not yet finished the job. We photographed both on the same morning. The stone refused to look its age. The sand, which is a kind of rumour about the stone, was already halfway to becoming something else by lunchtime, by way of the wind, which had begun to redistribute the dunes in a way that, by next year, would have made the photograph impossible."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Both",
          "eyebrow": "— SNOW & RAIN",
          "title": "Two Forms of Falling",
          "caption": "First snow at the high pass, last warm rain at the village square, photographed inside one week of October.",
          "folio": "p. 52",
          "body": "The first snow of October arrived a week before the last rain, which is a coincidence we cannot account for. We were photographing in the high pass when the snow began. By the time we drove down to the village in the evening, the rain was waiting at the square. They are, of course, the same weather, only at different temperatures. The snow falls patiently and waits to be looked at; the rain is in a hurry, and gets things wet, and is generally less photogenic. We made one frame in each. The negatives sit beside each other in the working archive, dated three days apart, and the difference between them is, in the end, only a question of altitude and afternoon."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Twin",
          "eyebrow": "— PINE & BIRCH",
          "title": "Two Kinds of Patience",
          "caption": "A stand of old pines on the north slope and a stand of young birch on the south slope, photographed inside the same hour.",
          "folio": "p. 56",
          "body": "The pines on the north side of the hill are at least three hundred years older than the birch on the south side. Both populations are doing their work with the same daylight; only the duration of the work has been different. The pines have been there long enough to have developed habits. The birch are still in their busy youth, putting on weight, dropping leaves, generally unsettled. We photographed both on the same afternoon. The pines, in the picture, are dignified and slightly bored. The birch are a small commotion. Neither, on its own, would say much about the hill. Together they describe a slope and three centuries, which is, on balance, more than we set out to record."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Pair",
          "eyebrow": "— RIDGE & VALLEY",
          "title": "What the Land Shows",
          "caption": "Ridge from the south face, valley floor from the same vantage, framed by a single afternoon's light.",
          "folio": "p. 60",
          "body": "From the south face of the ridge, you can see the valley floor for ten kilometres in either direction. We sat at the same outcrop and made two photographs, of the high country and the low country, without moving the tripod. The two frames, printed at the same scale, look like different planets. The ridge is austere, with very little growing on it; the valley is a busy green, full of fences and roads and, on a Tuesday, a slow tractor. We did not photograph the tractor. The picture is a more honest one without it. The ridge does not appear in the valley photograph, and the valley does not appear in the ridge photograph, but both pictures describe the same hour of light, falling, on the same hillside."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Two",
          "eyebrow": "— DAWN & DUSK",
          "title": "Two Hours, Same Coast",
          "caption": "East-facing cove at first light, west-facing cliffs at last light, the same coastline, the same calendar day.",
          "folio": "p. 64",
          "body": "On the same Sunday in May, we made two photographs at the two ends of the day. The east-facing cove at five-thirty in the morning, the west-facing cliffs at eight-thirty in the evening. The coastline, between the two exposures, was the same coastline. The light, by contrast, had moved from one side of the planet to the other. The morning picture has the slight green that very early light tends to lend to water; the evening one has the slight pink that late light gives to stone. The pictures hang at home in the order they were taken, and we still occasionally argue about which of the two we prefer, though by now we both know the argument has no resolution."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Both",
          "eyebrow": "— WAVE & WIND",
          "title": "What Moves the Surface",
          "caption": "Open ocean from the lighthouse balcony, mid-sized swell, ordinary southwesterly that came up at four.",
          "folio": "p. 68",
          "body": "The wind moves the water; the water moves itself. Most photographs of the sea record only the second of these two motions. We tried, that week, to photograph both — the wave that the water is making, and the wind that is making the wave. The trick is in the spray. Spray is what gives the wind a body, and a body is what makes the wind photographable. We stood for three hours at the lighthouse balcony, in conditions that were not, by any reasonable measure, pleasant. The negatives from that afternoon, when developed, finally showed the thing we had been after — wind and wave, in a single frame, each visible by way of the other."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
