      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 11",
          "title": "Echo & Reply",
          "kicker": "A duet from two photographers who shared a darkroom for one season but never published together.",
          "number": "11",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "Echo & Reply pairs work made by two photographers in the spring and autumn of the same year, in the same coastal town, without their being aware of each other's project. The discovery, made by an editor going through working prints two years later, was that they had photographed many of the same things — a single bench, a particular window, the corner of one café — and had reached, by independent means, almost identical compositions. The book is laid out in pairs. Their photographs sit on facing pages. The captions, by mutual agreement, do not identify which photographer made which frame, and the reader is left to guess, or, more often, to give up guessing."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 12",
          "title": "Salt / Sweet",
          "kicker": "Two photographers, one harbour, one bakery — paired studies in saline air and rising bread.",
          "number": "12",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "body": "Salt / Sweet is a paired portfolio: one photographer worked at the harbour, the other at the bakery on the square, both for the same six months. The decision to pair them was made late, by a third party, and required minor sequencing work — the harbour pictures were sequenced by tide, the bakery pictures by hour. In the printed book the two sequences run in parallel: a harbour plate on the left, a bakery plate on the right, paired by time of day. The photographers met for the first time at the launch. They agreed, with mild surprise, that the pairing held."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 13",
          "title": "North & South",
          "kicker": "Same continent, opposite coasts. Two photographers, two windows, one calendar year of weather.",
          "number": "13",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "North & South is a paired-window project. Two photographers, in two cities four thousand kilometres apart, agreed to make one photograph from one window every Sunday for fifty-two weeks. The windows face one another across the continent, and the resulting series, printed two-up, is a record of how differently a year passes in two latitudes. The book is divided into the four seasons. Each spread shows two Sundays, in the same week, from the two windows. The northern winter and the southern summer occupy the first quarter; the alignment reverses by midyear."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 14",
          "title": "Open & Close",
          "kicker": "Photographs of opening hours and closing hours, in two cafés on the same Marseille square.",
          "number": "14",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "body": "Open & Close is a study of the bookends of the working day. Two photographers split a single Marseille square between them: one photographed the café on the left at the moment it opened each morning; the other photographed the café on the right at the moment it closed each night. The two sequences, eighty-five mornings and eighty-five evenings, are sequenced by date and printed face-to-face. The square does not appear in either photograph. The clocks behind the counters, at opposite ends of the day, are the only consistent element."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 15",
          "title": "Day / Night",
          "kicker": "A single street, photographed at noon by one and at midnight by the other, every weekend in autumn.",
          "number": "15",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "Day / Night is a paired-time study. The street is the same street; the photographers are different people. One photographed at twelve in the afternoon, the other at twelve at night, every Saturday for the autumn of the working year. The book pairs each pair of frames on facing pages, in chronological order. Four prints, printed at the same scale, sit between the two photographers' working notes at the back of the volume. The notes were written without the writers having seen each other's photographs."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 16",
          "title": "Body & Building",
          "kicker": "Two photographers — one anatomist, one architect — pair the human form against the man-made line.",
          "number": "16",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "body": "Body & Building pairs a portfolio of figure studies against a portfolio of architectural studies. The photographers had not previously worked together; the editor proposed the pairing on the strength of a single coincidence — both had, in the same year, used the identical north-facing window of the same studio. The book is sequenced by light direction. The figures and the buildings, printed face-to-face, share a common geometry that neither photographer had set out to demonstrate. The captions are kept to one line each."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 17",
          "title": "Land & Light",
          "kicker": "A landscape photographer and a still-life photographer agreed, for six months, to swap subjects.",
          "number": "17",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "Land & Light documents a six-month exchange between two photographers who agreed, for the duration, to photograph each other's usual subject. The landscape photographer worked exclusively in a single studio with five objects on a table; the still-life photographer worked exclusively in the open countryside, without props. The book pairs their results, week by week, in chronological order. Both arrived at the same conclusion at roughly the same time: their original subjects had, after the swap, become unfamiliar in a way they were not entirely sure how to talk about."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 18",
          "title": "Pair One",
          "kicker": "The first volume in a series of paired editions. Two photographers who had never met before this collaboration.",
          "number": "18",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "Pair One is the inaugural volume of a paired series. The premise is simple: two photographers who have not previously met are given a single shared brief and a single working week, and the resulting work is published together without further editorial coordination. In this first edition the brief was: Photograph the room you are currently sitting in. The two photographers, separated by half a continent, did not see one another's work until the week was over and the contact sheets arrived simultaneously at the editor's desk."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 19",
          "title": "Twin Studies",
          "kicker": "Two photographers, blood relations, returning to the family house for the first time in fifteen years.",
          "number": "19",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "Twin Studies pairs the work of a brother and a sister returning to their parents' house after fifteen years away from it. They worked separately, on alternating days, for one week. Neither saw the other's photographs during the working period. The book is laid out in chronological pairs: brother on the left page, sister on the right, in the order the frames were made. They photographed the same eleven rooms. They agreed, in the introduction they later wrote together, that the photographs do not, on inspection, look like the work of the same household."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "PROJECT 20",
          "title": "Working / Resting",
          "kicker": "Two studios in the same building. One photographer always at work; the other only between projects.",
          "number": "20",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "Working / Resting is a paired portrait of two studios on adjacent floors of the same Berlin building. One photographer was, during the working period, between projects; the other was at the height of one. The book pairs their two studios on each spread, alternating hours of the day. The contrast between the two rooms — one busy, one almost empty — is the principal documentary observation. The photographers shared a coffee machine in the hallway, and a working agreement that neither would mention the project to the other for six months."
        }
      ],
