      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON CRAFT",
          "pullquote": "To know how is one thing; to know when is something else entirely.",
          "byline": "AFTER A. ADAMS",
          "caption": "Studio bench, late afternoon.",
          "folio": "p. 06",
          "body": "The hardest thing in any craft is the timing of it. Method can be taught; ripeness cannot. The photograph that wants to be made will arrive on its own schedule, and the photographer's job is to be prepared for it. Most of what we call practice is, on closer inspection, waiting. We learn the equipment, the chemistry, the habits of light, so that when the moment finally agrees to be photographed, we are not, as it were, fumbling with the buttons. The craft is the part that becomes invisible. The timing remains visible, in every frame, as the only thing that finally separates a working photographer from a person with a camera."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON HOME",
          "pullquote": "Some places we leave; others leave us. The departure is rarely mutual.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Family pasture, returning for the first time in nine years.",
          "folio": "p. 14",
          "body": "There is a kind of leaving that is, in the end, a kind of staying. We leave a place; the place stays in us. Years later, in another country, the smell of dry grass at four in the afternoon returns the entire summer of our twelfth year, intact. The place, by then, no longer exists in the form we knew it — the fence has been rebuilt, the barn has been pulled down, the dog has been buried under the apple tree — but the version we carry is, at this distance, more accurate than any photograph we ever made."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON COURAGE",
          "pullquote": "To photograph what frightens you is to admit, at last, that you have been looking.",
          "byline": "AFTER R. FRANK",
          "caption": "First trip alone, the second night.",
          "folio": "p. 22",
          "body": "The photograph you are afraid to make is, almost always, the one worth making. Fear is, in this craft, a reasonably accurate compass. It points at the thing the photographer has been avoiding, which is, more often than not, the centre of the working subject. Most photographers spend the first decade of their working life learning to recognise this, and the rest of their working life trying to act on it. The act, when it eventually arrives, is rarely heroic. It is a small unflinching, on a Tuesday morning, in front of a thing that no one has asked you to photograph."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON DISTANCE",
          "pullquote": "The closer you are, the less you see. The further away, the less you can change.",
          "byline": "AFTER E. WESTON",
          "caption": "View from the third bridge, in fog.",
          "folio": "p. 30",
          "body": "Every photographer must choose, eventually, where to stand. Closeness gives intimacy and removes context; distance gives context and removes the small detail. There is no correct answer to this problem. The honest photographers are the ones who have looked at it carefully, made a choice, and accepted what the choice has taken from them. The dishonest ones are the ones who claim that their distance, whichever it is, is the right one. Distance, in this craft, is the most morally weighted of the camera's settings."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON TIME",
          "pullquote": "The hour is the only thing the photographer cannot lie about.",
          "byline": "AFTER S. SONTAG",
          "caption": "Five o'clock, the third Wednesday in November.",
          "folio": "p. 38",
          "body": "You can lie about the subject, the location, the intention. You cannot lie about the hour. The light at four in the morning is not the light at four in the afternoon, and any photographer who tells you otherwise is, at best, mistaken. The honest photograph names its hour, even if the caption does not. The dishonest photograph attempts to disguise it. The dishonesty is rarely successful, because the eye, which has spent its entire life looking at light, is unusually well calibrated for the time of day, and is not easily fooled by even the most sincere darkroom work."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON MEMORY",
          "pullquote": "The photograph is not the memory. It is the fence the memory leans on.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Album shelf, second from the bottom.",
          "folio": "p. 46",
          "body": "A photograph and a memory are not the same thing, and the photograph is not, in any honest sense, a record of the memory. What the photograph records is something the memory then organises itself around. The relationship is structural rather than evidentiary. We tell the story of a summer with the help of three photographs, but the story is not in the photographs; it is in the joints between them, which are made of weather, and overheard conversation, and a particular kind of fatigue that does not come back from a print."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON SEASON",
          "pullquote": "Photograph the year; the day will follow.",
          "byline": "AFTER P. STRAND",
          "caption": "First frost, the orchard, before sunrise.",
          "folio": "p. 54",
          "body": "The day is too short a unit for serious photographic work. The week is, on most subjects, also too short. The year, by contrast, is about right. A year of photographs of a single subject — a tree, a window, a coastline — accumulates a kind of weight that no individual day can produce, and the photographer, by the end of it, has changed in ways the work makes visible. The reverse, of course, is also true: the work has changed in ways the photographer makes visible. There is no separating the two motions, and there is no shortcut to them."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON HONESTY",
          "pullquote": "The print does not argue with what the negative shows. The print argues with what we wish.",
          "byline": "AFTER A. ADAMS",
          "caption": "Working print, first attempt, set aside.",
          "folio": "p. 62",
          "body": "In the darkroom, the photographer's principal opponent is his or her own preference. The negative records what was there. The print, almost invariably, attempts to record what we wished had been there. The work of honest printing is, in large part, the work of letting the negative win the argument. The dishonest print imposes a mood. The honest print receives one. The difference between the two, on the page, is small. The difference between the two, in the photographer's career, is the entire difference, and it is rarely settled in a single afternoon."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON CHANGE",
          "pullquote": "A place keeps changing whether or not you photograph it. Your camera was never the point.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Family pasture, fifteen years on, in autumn light.",
          "folio": "p. 70",
          "body": "It is tempting, in the practice of a long project, to feel that the camera is doing the work of preservation. It is not. The place is changing whether or not the photographer is present. The work, in the end, is not preservation; it is, at most, attention. The photographer attends to the change for as long as he or she can, and accumulates a record, and the record is honest only insofar as it admits its own modesty. The pasture will be a parking lot in nine years. The photograph will not, by any honest measure, have prevented that. The photograph will, however, have witnessed it."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON COMPANY",
          "pullquote": "The best photographs are made when the photographer has, for once, forgotten to perform.",
          "byline": "AFTER R. FRANK",
          "caption": "Late evening, second-floor flat, the conversation paused.",
          "folio": "p. 78",
          "body": "The presence of other people changes the photographer in small, almost invisible ways. We are slightly more careful with our equipment when watched. We frame slightly more conventionally. We make, by an inch, the picture we think we are supposed to make. The photographer working alone is, usually, the more honest one — at least until he or she has been alone for long enough to remember an audience anyway. The frame in which the photographer has, briefly, forgotten that anyone might ever look at the picture is the frame that, almost always, turns out to have been worth making."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
