      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— TUESDAY 06:18",
          "title": "Two Streets at Six",
          "byline": "BY ROBERT WILLIAM",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "body": "The street that runs north on Tuesday morning is empty by six. The other street, three blocks east, is already busy — the bakery does its delivery at five forty-five and the corner café opens at six exactly. We walked between the two for a week, with one camera and no plan, and brought home most of a contact sheet that nobody has yet asked to see."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FRIDAY 23:47",
          "title": "Wet Pavement",
          "byline": "BY MAYA HALDEN",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "Rain in a city you don't know is the best invitation to walk slowly. The pavement does the work of a softbox. Headlights become brushes. Things you would not have noticed in dry weather are, on a wet Friday at midnight, suddenly the only things worth photographing. We made twelve frames that night and developed them at the kitchen sink in the morning, in a hotel that almost certainly should not have allowed it."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SUNDAY 02:14",
          "title": "Last Cigarette",
          "byline": "BY S. ARDEN",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "body": "The bar closes at two. The man at the corner table has bought a last cigarette he does not really want and has been holding it, unlit, for the past nine minutes. The photograph is one frame, made from across the room, while pretending to look at the menu. He is in it without knowing. He has, since, written to thank us for the print, having recognised himself in the catalogue, which is a complication we had not anticipated."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— WEDNESDAY 16:32",
          "title": "Empty Café",
          "byline": "BY E. SOLBAKKEN",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "Mid-afternoon, the wrong day of the week, and the café is empty for an hour between the lunch rush and the after-work crowd. The owner is reading the paper at the counter. The light is moving across the empty tables in a way that will not happen again until next Wednesday. We spent thirty minutes there, drinking coffee that had been on the warmer too long, and made the year's most reliable photograph."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— THURSDAY 22:15",
          "title": "After the Show",
          "byline": "BY T. MATSURA",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "body": "The crowd has gone. The cleaners have not arrived. The room is in the state of mild disarray that always follows a working evening. Plastic cups, programmes left on chairs, a single coat that someone will eventually come back for. We photograph at exactly this hour, between events, when no one is performing and no one is yet cleaning. The picture is rarely interesting on its own. Twelve of them in sequence become a kind of inventory of forgetfulness."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SATURDAY 23:58",
          "title": "Closing Hour",
          "byline": "BY P. ROSEN",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "The shop closes in two minutes. The owner is already counting the till. The last customer is debating, with himself, whether to commit to a small purchase he does not really need. The light from the open back room falls into the shop at an angle that is only available in the last two minutes of the day. We make one frame, pay for our chocolate, and leave before the man with the chocolate has decided."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— MONDAY 05:42",
          "title": "Old Hotel",
          "byline": "BY M. OYEDEPO",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "The lobby of an old hotel, forty minutes before the desk clerk arrives, is one of the more honest rooms in any city. The night porter has gone home. The plants have not been watered for the day. The clock on the wall is, as it always is, four minutes wrong, and nobody has been here to disagree with it for the past hour. We sat on the wrong sofa and read the wrong newspaper and made the day's first picture."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— TUESDAY 21:30",
          "title": "Train Station",
          "byline": "BY J. AKINOLA",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "A small station between two larger ones is busiest at half past nine in the evening, when the connecting trains briefly meet. For ninety seconds the platform holds people from four different cities. Then the trains leave in opposite directions, and the platform is empty for the next forty-three minutes. We have photographed both states — the brief crowd, and the long emptiness. They sit on facing pages and the platform, in the printed book, has not changed at all."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FRIDAY 19:08",
          "title": "Bridge at Night",
          "byline": "BY V. ATALA",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "A pedestrian bridge, lit from beneath, in the half-hour after the office workers have all crossed and before the evening crowd has begun to. The river is doing its slow business below, and the city has put its lights on in patches that have nothing to do with one another. We stand at the centre and photograph in both directions. The two frames look like different cities entirely."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SUNDAY 11:00",
          "title": "City Window",
          "byline": "BY R. KAUFMANN",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "body": "From the kitchen window of a friend's flat, on a Sunday morning, the city looks like the kind of city that has never had Mondays. People walk slowly, in the wrong direction. A child runs past with a balloon, and the balloon is not a metaphor. We photograph the street from the third floor and put down the camera, because the picture has been made, and the rest of the morning belongs to coffee and to the slow drift of conversation."
        }
      ],
