      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 01",
          "title": "Tokyo & Kyoto",
          "byline": "BY HEN. CHAE",
          "caption": "Two morning routines, four hundred kilometres apart, on the same Wednesday in May.",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "Tokyo wakes by being interrupted; Kyoto wakes by being asked. The two cities are connected by an excellent train and almost nothing else. We made one frame in each, on the same Wednesday morning in May, at exactly six o'clock. The Tokyo picture is full of people walking quickly in opposite directions; the Kyoto picture is mostly stone, with one priest crossing it. Both are accurate. Neither, on its own, is sufficient. The pair, at the catalogue scale, is what we mean when we talk about that month."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 02",
          "title": "Paris, Paris",
          "byline": "BY ROBERT WILLIAM",
          "caption": "Same square, twelve hours apart. Forenoon and forenight.",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "body": "The Place des Vosges is two different squares, depending on the hour. At eleven in the morning it is full of strollers, students reading on the benches, the occasional tourist who has read the guidebook. At eleven at night it is empty, the lights are honey-coloured, and the sound of a single bicycle is louder than any of the daytime noise. We made the two frames a year apart, by accident, and only realised the pairing on the contact sheet."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 03",
          "title": "Rome & Florence",
          "byline": "BY MAYA HALDEN",
          "caption": "The same Tuesday, two trains apart, two espressos behaved differently.",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "Rome is, in the politest possible sense, a city that has never apologised for itself. Florence apologises constantly, and charmingly, for being slightly less. The two cities are an hour and a half apart by train and a century apart in temperament. We had a single Tuesday in May to spend on both, and we spent the morning in Rome and the afternoon in Florence, and the espresso in each city behaved according to type."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 04",
          "title": "Lisbon & Porto",
          "byline": "BY S. ARDEN",
          "caption": "Two hills, two views, two glasses of the same wine in two different blue tiles.",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "body": "Lisbon and Porto are siblings, not twins. They share most of their grammar but have arrived at different conclusions about volume. Lisbon is louder, sunnier, and a little more performative. Porto is the older sibling who has decided, without making a fuss about it, that quiet is fine. We spent five days in each, drank the same wine in both, and brought back two photographs that we have, ever since, hung side by side."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 05",
          "title": "Two Italian Cafés",
          "byline": "BY E. SOLBAKKEN",
          "caption": "One in Trieste, one in Naples — same drink, two languages.",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "The two cafés are seven hundred kilometres apart and serve almost identical espresso. The conversations, at the counter, are entirely different. In Trieste the customers complain about the wind and the bureaucracy, in roughly that order. In Naples they complain about the football and the football, also in that order. The espresso is a small and steady fact between two larger arguments, and we have photographed both, on different visits, in light that was nearly the same."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 06",
          "title": "Berlin & Vienna",
          "byline": "BY R. KAUFMANN",
          "caption": "Two cafés, two coats, two ways of being in February.",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "body": "Berlin in February has a particular cold that goes through the wool of any coat in the city. Vienna in February has the same temperature on paper and an entirely different one in practice — the cafés are warmer, the streets are quieter, the sunshine, when it does arrive, is taken seriously. We spent a week in each, on either side of a long train ride, and the two photographs from that fortnight share only the temperature."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 07",
          "title": "Two Markets, Marrakech",
          "byline": "BY M. OYEDEPO",
          "caption": "Morning souk and evening market, both in the same square, four hours apart.",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "The square in central Marrakech is two markets a day. By morning it is mostly food and shoes; by evening it is mostly food and music. The two markets are connected by a brief, chaotic two o'clock during which the morning vendors leave and the evening ones arrive. We photographed both, on the same Friday, with a four-hour interval that was spent reading in a riad. The two pictures, side by side, are nearly the same square, on the same date, with two entirely different populations."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 08",
          "title": "Stockholm & Helsinki",
          "byline": "BY I. BJÖRK",
          "caption": "Two ferries, one sea, eighteen hours of crossing in mid-November.",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "The overnight ferry from Stockholm to Helsinki is the closest thing the Baltic has to a habit. By the time the boat docks at half past nine in the morning, you have crossed eight hours of dark water and arrived in a different language. The two cities, photographed at twilight from the harbour, have almost identical light and very different architectures. We have travelled both directions, on consecutive Novembers, and the two pictures are, in the catalogue, dated a year apart and labelled identically."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 09",
          "title": "Two Lakes",
          "byline": "BY P. ROSEN",
          "caption": "Como at first light, Garda at last light, photographed inside one Tuesday in October.",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "The Italian lakes are not interchangeable, despite what the brochures suggest. Como is steeper, more mannered, and slightly self-conscious about its own popularity. Garda is broader, less polite, and behaves as though no one were ever watching. We made one frame at each in the same Tuesday in October, drove between the two during the working day, and were back at the hotel by ten in the evening, with two negatives that look like they were made on different continents."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— PAIRED CITIES 10",
          "title": "Coast & City",
          "byline": "BY V. ATALA",
          "caption": "The wild coast outside Lisbon and the city centre, the same afternoon, an hour's drive apart.",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "The coast outside Lisbon is forty minutes' drive and a different hemisphere. The city is busy and elegant; the coast is loud and indifferent. We left Belém at one and were standing at Cabo da Roca by two, in conditions that did not, on either end of the journey, allow for a leisurely lunch. The two photographs from that afternoon — one of the city, one of the cliffs — pair the human-made with the wholly otherwise, on the same Iberian Tuesday in late autumn."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
