      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH ROBERT WILLIAM ON A QUIET LIGHT",
          "caption": "Robert William at his coastal studio, autumn light through the north window, the second hour of the working morning.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "On Slow Looking",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "folio_2": "p. 09",
          "body": "Robert William is, by his own admission, not a fast worker. The four months that produced A Quiet Light are, in his account, mostly an experiment in not trying very hard. We met at the studio in late October, in the second hour of his working morning, with the kettle on. The conversation that followed was, in the way of these conversations, mostly about everything except the photographs. He has lived in this town for fourteen years, four of them in the studio, the rest in a small flat above a bakery on the next street. The studio faces north, has a single uninsulated window, and is, by his own description, the least practical room he has ever rented. It is also, he says without irony, the only room he has ever made anything good in. He works in the mornings, drinks coffee for the first hour, and rarely loads a camera before nine. The book, he insists, was made by the room, not by him. We do not entirely believe him, but the room does most of the talking."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH MAYA HALDEN ON SURFACE",
          "caption": "Maya Halden at the studio in Reykjavik, working print on the easel, the year's first frost on the morning of the visit.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "The Wall as Subject",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "folio_2": "p. 13",
          "body": "Maya Halden's working studio in Reykjavik is the size of a generous bathroom and gets less light. The decision to photograph against this constraint, rather than against it, was made early. SURFACE, the resulting portfolio, is forty close studies of materials photographed under raking light from a single high window. We met on a morning in late November, the year's first frost still on the courtyard outside. The studio was warm in the way that very small rooms are warm — too warm, almost — and the kettle had been on for a while. Halden talks about her work the way other people talk about their commute: with patience, without ceremony, and with the suspicion that no one really wants to hear about it. We persisted. The interview, in its working length, ran for nearly four hours, of which roughly twenty minutes were on the record."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH S. ARDEN ON DRIFT",
          "caption": "S. Arden at the boat-shed by the river, working notebook open on the bench, the working boat tied up beyond.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "Twelve Days, One River",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "folio_2": "p. 17",
          "body": "S. Arden's DRIFT was photographed from a small wooden boat over twelve consecutive days in July. The boat is still in working order, tied up at the shed where we met her in early September. The shed smells of varnish and the river. The river itself is, on the morning of the visit, almost still, in conditions Arden describes as nearly identical to the eighth day of the project. She talks about the work with the slight bemusement of a photographer who has not entirely decided whether the working method was, in retrospect, brave or merely lucky. The conversation lasts nearly three hours, of which the first half is mostly about the boat and the second half mostly about light. The photographs themselves come up only briefly, near the end, when we ask her to choose a working print to look at together. She declines, politely, and offers us coffee instead, which we accept."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH E. SOLBAKKEN ON HOUR BLUE",
          "caption": "E. Solbakken at the apartment window, the same window that produced the entire HOUR BLUE archive, in late afternoon.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "One Window, Three Hundred and Sixty-Five",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "folio_2": "p. 21",
          "body": "E. Solbakken's HOUR BLUE was made from a single window over the course of one calendar year. We met at the apartment in early March, with the year's working archive complete, the project's last evening having been four months earlier. The window is in the corner of the kitchen, small, north-facing, and unremarkable in every recordable respect except that it has produced three hundred and sixty-five photographs. Solbakken made coffee while talking, in the manner of a person who has had this conversation often enough to know roughly how long it lasts. The window itself looks out over a square that, on the morning of the visit, was occupied by a single child kicking a football against an iron bench. The interview, when transcribed, ran to roughly fifteen thousand words, of which we kept perhaps two thousand."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH T. MATSURA ON SALT AND IRON",
          "caption": "T. Matsura at the harbour, the same quay from which the SALT AND IRON sequence was made, with the working boats moored.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "At the Edges of the Day",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "folio_2": "p. 25",
          "body": "T. Matsura's SALT AND IRON was photographed at a single working harbour over the course of a season, in the half-hour before sunrise and the half-hour after sunset. We met him at the harbour itself, on a quiet Tuesday morning in late October, with the season's last working trips already concluded and the boats mostly moored. Matsura is older than his photographs and speaks Japanese with the slight English accent of a man who has lived abroad for a long time. He worked on the docks himself, in his late twenties, and remembers the harbour from the inside, which is, in his account, the entire reason for the project. The conversation lasts most of a morning, drifts through three different cafés, and is interrupted twice by visiting friends, both of whom have known Matsura for over thirty years and who, in his account, are unimpressed by the project."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH P. ROSEN ON SLOW GLASS",
          "caption": "P. Rosen in the field where the SLOW GLASS exposures were made, the abandoned farmhouse just visible beyond.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "What the Window Saw",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "folio_2": "p. 29",
          "body": "P. Rosen's SLOW GLASS is a portfolio of nine very long exposures, made through old window panes in derelict houses. The shortest exposure was forty minutes. The longest was seventy-two minutes. We met him at the field where the third plate was made, in late October, with the abandoned farmhouse still standing at the far end of it. Rosen, in conversation, is reluctant to elaborate. The method, he says, is its own argument. The hardest part of the project was, in his account, not the camera but the tripod, which had to be kept exactly still for over an hour at a stretch and which, on at least two occasions, was knocked over by deer in the working field."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH M. OYEDEPO ON UNTITLED (GARDEN)",
          "caption": "M. Oyedepo in the garden that produced the entire two-year project, late winter, the lavender still cut back.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "A Garden Year",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "folio_2": "p. 33",
          "body": "M. Oyedepo's UNTITLED (GARDEN) is a deliberately uneventful project — one small garden, photographed weekly, for two years. We met her in the garden itself, in late February, before the year's third working week. The garden is twelve square metres. The lavender, on the morning of the visit, had been cut back to its winter form. Oyedepo made coffee in the kitchen and brought it out to the garden bench, which is the same bench from which the entire project was photographed. She talks about the work with a kind of patient amusement, as a person might talk about a project that has, by lasting two years, become a piece of furniture in her life."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH J. AKINOLA ON NORTH LIGHT",
          "caption": "J. Akinola at the studio under the north window that produced the entire NORTH LIGHT portrait series.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "Sixteen Sittings",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "folio_2": "p. 37",
          "body": "J. Akinola's NORTH LIGHT is sixteen portraits made under the same studio window. We met him at the studio in late spring, with the working period concluded and the working window unchanged. The studio is small. The window is north-facing. The chair is in the same position that it occupied during all sixteen sittings, and Akinola has, on his own admission, become slightly superstitious about not moving it. He is younger than his work suggests and talks about it with the slight self-consciousness of a photographer who has not yet entirely decided whether the work is good. We disagree, politely, but he is unconvinced. The conversation lasts most of an afternoon, of which the most useful hour is, by general agreement, the third."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH V. ATALA ON ARCHITECTURE OF AIR",
          "caption": "V. Atala at the conference room that produced PLATE 09 — the chairs as they were on the working morning.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "The Empty Room",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "folio_2": "p. 41",
          "body": "V. Atala's ARCHITECTURE OF AIR is a portfolio of architectural interiors, all photographed in the unoccupied state. We met him at the conference room in which Plate 9 was made, on the morning of the working visit, the chairs left in approximately the previous evening's configuration. Atala is, in conversation, unusually quiet. He uses the word ROOM in the way other photographers might use the word LIGHT — as the most important variable in any working frame. The interview lasts nearly three hours, much of it spent in the room itself, with the morning slowly changing the available light. He chose, late in the conversation, to allow us to photograph him in the room he had photographed; the resulting portrait is the only frame in this issue not made by Atala himself."
        },
        {
          "runninghead": "FEATURE · INTERVIEW · WITH THE GROUP ON LAST HOUR",
          "caption": "Editorial group at the year-end exhibition, three of the ten contributors not in attendance, the working light at six.",
          "eyebrow": "— ESSAY",
          "title": "Ten Photographers, One Hour",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "folio_2": "p. 45",
          "body": "LAST HOUR collects work made in the closing sixty minutes of an ordinary day, by ten contributors across four cities. Seven of the ten were in attendance at the year-end exhibition where we met them; the other three sent statements by email. The working brief, agreed by the editorial group, was minimal: photograph in the last hour of an ordinary day, in any city, with no other constraint. The resulting portfolio is, by collective agreement, the most uneven the editorial group has produced — which is, also by collective agreement, the most honest thing it could be. The conversation that followed the exhibition lasted three hours, drifted through four bars, and ended in a kitchen at one in the morning, in the manner of all good editorial conversations."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
