      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Saturday Light",
          "byline": "BY KARL VEGA",
          "vertical": "Note",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "Saturday Light came out of a very small mistake. I had agreed, in late winter, to spend a year photographing one small district of the city, and I had assumed, foolishly, that I would do most of the work on weekdays. By the third month I had photographed almost nothing. The district was at its quietest exactly when I had time to look at it, and I had been looking at quietness for so long that I had stopped seeing anything at all. The fix arrived by accident. A friend asked me to spend a Saturday with him. I brought the camera, more out of habit than intention. The district at noon on a Saturday was a different city. The shopkeepers were sweeping. The bakery had a queue. A child on a bicycle was being chased, with great dignity, by a much older dog. I made forty frames before lunch. The series, by the end of the year, was forty-eight Saturdays."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Twelve Hands",
          "byline": "BY ASHA MENDELSSOHN",
          "vertical": "Hands",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "Twelve Hands began with a violin maker in Cremona. I had gone there for a week to write something else and ended up watching, for nearly an hour, a pair of hands carving a scroll. The hands were patient and very small. The face above them, when I finally looked up, was almost incidental. The face was just a face. The hands had decades of specific information in them. I asked, that evening, whether I might come back the next morning with a camera, and I photographed only the hands, working, for the better part of three days. The series eventually included eleven other makers — a baker in Lyon, a bookbinder in Mexico City, a calligrapher in Kyoto, an instrument repairer in Berlin, and so on — chosen, in each case, because their hands had become, by long use, smarter than the rest of them."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Bicycle Year",
          "byline": "BY REN FUYUKO",
          "vertical": "Bike",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "Bicycle Year was, on its surface, an exercise in commute. I bought a small camera that fit in the front basket and made one photograph every morning, for a calendar year, on the route between my flat and the studio. The route was eleven minutes long. There was no rule against repetition. The interest, in the end, was not in the route but in the slow accumulation of a single year of weather, traffic, and the small, almost invisible changes a city undergoes between January and the following January. By the seventh month I knew the dogs by sight. By the ninth month, the dogs knew me back. By the year's end I had three hundred and sixty-five photographs, of which roughly thirty are good and ten are, in my opinion, the best work I have made."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Rooms with Doors Closed",
          "byline": "BY PIETER DROST",
          "vertical": "Rooms",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "Rooms with Doors Closed was a portfolio of hotel rooms photographed only after their guests had left and before the housekeeping staff had arrived. The window of opportunity was, on most days, less than thirty minutes. I worked in twenty-two hotels over the course of a single year. The hotel managers were, on the whole, more cooperative than I had expected. The work itself was repetitive — the rooms had the same furniture, the same mass-produced art, the same configuration of curtain and bed. The differences, when they emerged, were small and human: a forgotten earring on the desk, a folded piece of paper in the bin, a bath towel in a position that suggested a particular kind of hurry. The portfolio is concerned with these small private signals, which the rooms had been holding, briefly, before being reset."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Listening Hours",
          "byline": "BY LOU BERNER",
          "vertical": "Listen",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "Listening Hours is a portrait of seven musicians at home, photographed during their working practice, with their permission. The premise was simple: a single hour, in their usual practice space, with no instruction beyond that I would not interrupt. The musicians were, at first, slightly self-conscious. Most of them got over it within ten minutes; one of them never quite did, and the photographs of her are, by general agreement, the most interesting in the book. The work was photographed without flash, at the available light of each room. The instruments are visible in some frames and absent from others. The musicians, when I sent them their portraits months later, were almost all surprised by the same thing — they had not realised, while playing, that their faces were doing what the photographs eventually showed."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Heat Wave",
          "byline": "BY INES TARRAS",
          "vertical": "Heat",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "body": "Heat Wave was photographed in the August of a year that broke several local records. I had not intended to make a project about heat. The project announced itself by way of the equipment — film, in temperatures of forty-two degrees, behaves in ways that are not predictable, and I had spent the first week of the month fighting the medium and producing nothing. By the second week I had stopped fighting it. The film's small unreliabilities became part of the photograph. The towns I worked in — five of them, all in the same southern Spanish province — emptied between two and seven in the afternoon. The streets were narrow, white, and entirely without people. The shutters were closed. The photographs from those hours are the loudest ones in the portfolio, despite there being almost nothing in them."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Forecast",
          "byline": "BY OWEN MARAMBA",
          "vertical": "Sky",
          "folio": "p. 52",
          "body": "Forecast began as a research assignment. I had been hired, briefly, to make working photographs at a small atmospheric monitoring station in the Hebrides. The station was unmanned for most of the year and produced an enormous archive of automatic readings: temperature, wind direction, humidity, cloud type. I was paid, for three days, to photograph the equipment for a brochure. I stayed eleven days. The instruments turned out to be more interesting than the brochure had anticipated, and the weather they were monitoring became, in the photographs, the more honest subject. The portfolio sequences a year of unmanned readings against the weather they recorded. I did not return to the station after those eleven days. I have, on at least three subsequent occasions, considered it."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Slow Trains",
          "byline": "BY YUNA KJELLBERG",
          "vertical": "Rail",
          "folio": "p. 60",
          "body": "Slow Trains was made on long-distance trains in Eastern Europe, all of them ten hours or longer, all of them with sleeper compartments, none of them direct. The shortest journey in the project was eleven hours and forty minutes; the longest was thirty-eight hours, with two scheduled changes. I worked alone. The compartment of a long-distance train is a peculiar kind of room — temporary, semi-public, lit by a single weak bulb at night and by an unreliable parade of windows by day. The portfolio is mostly of the windows, which are, after all, the train's principal entertainment. The other passengers consented to being photographed in some cases, and chose not to in others, and the resulting work is therefore an honest document of who agrees to be looked at on a long train and who does not."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On After Service",
          "byline": "BY DIEGO ROSO",
          "vertical": "Empty",
          "folio": "p. 68",
          "body": "After Service is a portfolio of churches photographed in the half-hour after the morning service has ended. The premise emerged by accident. I had attended a service for entirely personal reasons, in a small church in northern Italy, and stayed afterwards because I had nowhere particular to be. The church, with the congregation gone, was a different room. The candles were still burning. A single woman was tidying the hymnals at the back. The light through the rose window was the same light that had been there an hour earlier, but now there was no audience for it. I made one photograph that morning, and another two weeks later in a different church, and a third the month after that. The portfolio eventually contained twenty-two churches, in eight countries, and I have not yet attended a service since the last one."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ARTIST'S NOTE",
          "title": "On Year of Tuesdays",
          "byline": "BY HANNAH OTT",
          "vertical": "Self",
          "folio": "p. 76",
          "body": "Year of Tuesdays is a self-portrait series. Every Tuesday, for a calendar year, I made one photograph of myself in the same chair, in the same room, at the same hour. The chair is a small green armchair that does not belong to me; it belonged to my grandmother, and it is on indefinite loan from her flat in another city. The room is my own. The hour was four in the afternoon. The exception was one Tuesday in late August, when I was travelling, and the photograph from that week was made in a hotel room in another country, in a different chair, at the same hour. The portfolio is, by my own admission, not flattering. I have aged a noticeable amount over the working year. The chair, by contrast, looks identical in all fifty-two frames, which is, in the end, the most useful comparison the project produced."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
