      },
      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 12",
          "kicker": "Photographs from a year that did not behave the way the forecasts said.",
          "title": "After the Flood",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "This is the twelfth issue of the magazine, and it has taken nearly two years to make. The original brief — to publish photographs from the months following a particular flood, in a particular town, by a particular photographer — was abandoned in the third month. The photographer kept working, the town kept changing, and what was supposed to be a quick documentary edit became, instead, a longer and more uneven account of what a place looks like when it is, slowly, rebuilding itself. The result is in your hands. The introductions in this issue are, by editorial preference, kept short. The photographs do most of the talking."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 13",
          "kicker": "Long-form work in three movements, by photographers who work slowly.",
          "title": "Slow Cinema",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "Slow Cinema is the magazine's first multi-photographer special issue. Three contributors agreed, at the start of the year, to photograph the same subject — the closing hour of one ordinary working day — for one month each. The resulting portfolios sit alongside one another in this issue, in the chronological order in which they were made. The differences are not what we expected. The similarities, by contrast, are larger than we expected, and they are visible whether or not the reader is paying attention. The introductory text from each photographer is included in full, by request."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 14",
          "kicker": "One photographer walked thirty kilometres a day, for over a hundred days.",
          "title": "The Long Walk",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "The Long Walk is, by some measure, the most strenuous project the magazine has commissioned. The contributor walked, on average, thirty kilometres a day for one hundred and twelve consecutive days through northern winter weather, in conditions that would not, by any reasonable assessment, be considered photographically friendly. The portfolio is the result. The contributor declined to be interviewed for this issue and chose, in the introductory text, to focus on the equipment rather than the journey. We respect both choices, and the portfolio speaks, in our editorial view, more clearly without further annotation."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 15",
          "kicker": "A photographic record of a phenomenon that does not behave the same way twice.",
          "title": "Northern Lights",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "Northern Lights is a special issue dedicated to the long photographic project of one contributor who has, for the past nine years, been making a single working trip to the same Norwegian inn for two weeks each February. The portfolio is the resulting accumulation. The lights, on most of the working evenings, did not appear; on the evenings when they did, the contributor was, by his own admission, often too tired or too cold to operate the camera competently. The forty frames in the portfolio are a small fraction of the working archive."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 16",
          "kicker": "Urban wildlife — foxes, gulls, rats — photographed only after dark.",
          "title": "City Animals",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "City Animals is, on its face, a documentary issue. The photographers, six of them, were each given the same brief — to photograph an animal in a city, after dark, in a single working week. The animals chosen were not specified by us. Three of the contributors picked foxes, two picked gulls, and one picked a colony of rats living in the canal of a particular European city. The resulting portfolios are mostly nocturnal, mostly available-light, and mostly unsentimental, which is the editorial preference of this magazine."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 17",
          "kicker": "Photographs from beneath the waterline. None in colour, none in clarity.",
          "title": "Underwater",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "Underwater is the magazine's first attempt at a sub-aquatic issue, and it has taken almost three years to put together. The brief, agreed with the four contributors, was that the photographs would all be made in conditions of poor visibility — turbid lake water, harbour silt, kelp forests — and that the technical challenges would not be removed in post-processing. The resulting portfolio is, in places, almost abstract. We did not commission a colour issue. The contributors all chose, independently, to work in monochrome, and the editorial decision was to honour that choice."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 18",
          "kicker": "Self-portraits by the artists, in domestic settings, one calendar year.",
          "title": "First Person",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "First Person is a self-portrait issue. The seven contributors agreed, at the start of the year, to make at least one self-portrait per month, in a domestic setting of their choosing, with no other constraint. The resulting portfolios are not, in the editorial view, particularly flattering. They are, however, accurate, and the magazine has chosen to publish the work in the order it was received, without further sequencing. The introductory texts in this issue are written by the contributors themselves and have not been edited."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 19",
          "kicker": "Working photographs from seven small restaurant kitchens in unusual cities.",
          "title": "Kitchen Sessions",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "Kitchen Sessions is a documentary issue produced in collaboration with a restaurant journal whose editorial board we have come to know over the past several years. The seven kitchens were not chosen for their fame. The contributors were given the brief of photographing the kitchen at three specific hours of the working day — eleven, four, and ten — and the resulting portfolios are, by editorial design, sequenced by hour rather than by kitchen. The recipes are not in this issue. They will appear, by mutual arrangement, in the journal's next issue."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 20",
          "kicker": "Twentieth issue. Photographs from the closing sixty minutes of a working day.",
          "title": "Last Light",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "This is the twentieth issue, and the editorial board has chosen to mark it with a portfolio that returns to the magazine's earliest premise — that there is, in any working day, a particular and reliably photographable hour. The ten contributors all agreed, in advance, to work only in the closing sixty minutes, and not to coordinate with one another. The resulting collective portfolio is the longest single-themed issue we have published. The introduction, by editorial choice, is by the youngest of the contributors, who joined the magazine's roster only this year."
        },
        {
          "masthead": "ISSUE 21",
          "kicker": "Quiet unoccupied rooms, by photographers known for working with figures.",
          "title": "Quiet Spaces",
          "folio": "p. 02",
          "body": "Quiet Spaces is a special issue contributed by photographers whose usual working practice involves figures. The brief, agreed with the seven contributors, was that for the duration of the working period they would not include a single human figure in the frame. Several of the contributors found the constraint harder than they expected; two of them eventually withdrew, and the editorial board has accepted those withdrawals without further comment. The portfolios in this issue are, in the magazine's editorial view, among the strongest collective work we have published in the past two years."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
