      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON STRUCTURE",
          "pullquote": "Composition is what the picture remembers when the photographer has stopped looking.",
          "byline": "AFTER P. STRAND",
          "caption": "Working print, the third negative on the second roll, edition print.",
          "folio": "p. 06",
          "body": "Structure in a photograph is the part that survives the photographer's intention. We make a frame; the frame, soon enough, makes us irrelevant. The strongest compositions are the ones that have stopped requiring our consent. They have organised themselves into a shape that the eye reads as inevitable. The photographer, in the working print, is no longer the author of the frame; he or she has become, at most, the witness who happened to be holding the camera at the moment the picture decided to organise itself."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON SCALE",
          "pullquote": "The smallest photograph in the room is, more often than not, the one I keep going back to.",
          "byline": "AFTER R. AVEDON",
          "caption": "Postcard print, four by six, retained for personal archive.",
          "folio": "p. 14",
          "body": "Photographic scale is the most over-discussed and least-understood variable in the practice. Big prints command rooms. Small prints command afternoons. The argument that a photograph wants to be seen at a particular size is, more often than not, an argument about the photograph's confidence rather than its content. A small print on a kitchen wall, looked at three times a week for ten years, accumulates a meaning that a museum-scale exhibition print rarely manages. The choice of scale is, in the end, a choice about how the photograph would like to be lived with."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON RHYTHM",
          "pullquote": "A series is not a list of frames. A series is a piece of music that keeps changing keys.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Working sequence, the third edit, abandoned for the fourth.",
          "folio": "p. 22",
          "body": "Sequencing is the part of photographic work that has the most in common with music. The order of the frames is, in any working portfolio, the most consequential editorial decision. The wrong order kills a body of work. The right order makes the same frames into something larger than themselves. The skill, when it is acquired, is acquired late. Most photographers do their best sequencing work after they have stopped trying to be photographers, by which point the rhythm has become more important to them than any individual frame."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON CONSTRAINT",
          "pullquote": "The most generous gift a photographer can give a project is a single, slightly arbitrary rule.",
          "byline": "AFTER B. EVANS",
          "caption": "Brief from the working notebook, the third week of the project.",
          "folio": "p. 30",
          "body": "Constraint is the working photographer's most reliable creative tool. A single small rule — only Tuesdays, only with one lens, only between five and six in the morning — does the kind of editorial work that no committee can produce. The constraint, by removing certain choices, forces the photographer's attention onto the choices that remain. It also produces, in any honest practitioner, a slight irritation that turns out to be the project's most useful raw material. The photographers who are reluctant to constrain their work are, almost always, the ones whose work fails to develop a recognisable voice."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON ATTENTION",
          "pullquote": "To photograph anything well, you must first stop trying to photograph it.",
          "byline": "AFTER M. C. CARTIER-BRESSON",
          "caption": "Working sketch, the second day of the visit, abandoned.",
          "folio": "p. 38",
          "body": "The photographer's attention is, like the human attention generally, slightly self-defeating. The harder we look, the more we tend to overlook. The frame that finally arrives, in any honest project, almost always arrives during a brief lapse in concentration — a moment of fatigue, of conversation, of giving up. The discipline of practice is, paradoxically, the discipline of arranging the conditions in which one's own attention is allowed to fail. The photographer who never lets her attention rest produces, in the end, only diligent work."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON PROCESS",
          "pullquote": "The work is the part that remains after every preference has been overruled by what the negative shows.",
          "byline": "FROM THE DARKROOM NOTES",
          "caption": "Working print, fifth attempt, the night the heating broke.",
          "folio": "p. 46",
          "body": "Process, in photographic practice, is the long argument between what we wished and what the medium recorded. The argument is not, on most working evenings, won. The print we eventually keep is rarely the print we set out to make; it is, rather, the print the negative was prepared to give us. The honest photographer learns, over the working years, to lose the argument gracefully. The dishonest one tries, with increasing determination, to win, and produces, by the end, only a long career of small misrepresentations of the available material."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON FAILURE",
          "pullquote": "The best frames in any working archive are surrounded, on all sides, by the failures that produced them.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Contact sheet, the working week, the keepers circled in red.",
          "folio": "p. 54",
          "body": "Failure, in the working practice, is not the opposite of success; it is the medium through which success is approached. A working portfolio of forty good photographs is, almost without exception, the surviving fraction of a working archive of four hundred. The bad frames are not waste. They are the rough material from which the good frames eventually emerge. A photographer who has never produced a long stretch of bad work has, almost always, also failed to produce work of any consequence. The two outcomes are connected by a single craft."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON STARTING",
          "pullquote": "The first frame of any project is, on average, the worst one. The photographer should make it anyway.",
          "byline": "AFTER R. ARBUS",
          "caption": "First exposure of the working project, retained in the archive.",
          "folio": "p. 62",
          "body": "Starting a project is harder than finishing one, and it gets no easier with practice. The first frame is, in almost every working case, the weakest. The honest practitioner makes it anyway, knowing that the first frame's only useful function is to permit the second one. A surprising number of unfinished projects in any working archive failed not at the level of execution but at the level of beginning. The photograph that was never made — because the photographer was waiting for the right conditions — is, in the end, indistinguishable from the project that was never undertaken."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON FINISHING",
          "pullquote": "A project is finished when the photographer is no longer surprised by anything the working archive contains.",
          "byline": "FROM THE NOTEBOOKS",
          "caption": "Final edit, the eighteenth working print, after the fourth re-sequence.",
          "folio": "p. 70",
          "body": "Finishing a project is, paradoxically, more difficult than starting one. The temptation, at the close of any working period, is to keep adding frames in the hope of improving the portfolio's average. The temptation is almost always wrong. The portfolio, at a certain point, is finished, and the additional frames diminish the work rather than reinforce it. The signal, in any honest practice, is the photographer's own boredom with the working archive. When nothing in the archive surprises us anymore, the project is closed. The closing is rarely ceremonious."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— ON REPETITION",
          "pullquote": "Photograph the same thing fifty times. The fiftieth frame will tell you what the first one was about.",
          "byline": "AFTER E. WESTON",
          "caption": "Working print, the fiftieth attempt at the same composition.",
          "folio": "p. 78",
          "body": "Repetition is, in photographic work, the slowest and most reliable teacher. The first photograph of a subject tells us, on average, almost nothing. The tenth tells us that we are committed. The fiftieth tells us, by accumulation, what the first photograph was reaching for. Most working photographers do not have the patience for this. The ones who do tend to produce, over a long career, a body of work that has the appearance of having been thought through, even when, in reality, it was simply repeated until it became thought."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
