      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 01",
          "title": "Morning, Noon, Evening",
          "caption": "Three photographs of the same balcony, the same Tuesday in May, taken at first light, midday, and last light.",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "The balcony is the same balcony. The Tuesday is the same Tuesday. The light, between the three frames, is the only thing that has moved. The morning is cold and slightly green. The noon is bleached and almost colourless. The evening, by contrast, finally allows the building across the street to cast a shadow."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 02",
          "title": "Spring, Summer, Autumn",
          "caption": "Three photographs of the same orchard, three months apart, in the same hour and with the same lens.",
          "folio": "p. 08",
          "body": "The orchard is the same orchard. The seasons, between the three frames, do all the photograph's work. The spring frame is white and surprised. The summer frame is loud. The autumn frame is dignified — the leaves have begun to fall, and the orchard appears, briefly, to have decided to listen."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 03",
          "title": "North, South, East",
          "caption": "Three photographs from the same rooftop, on the same evening, looking in three of the four cardinal directions.",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "The rooftop is the same rooftop. The evening is the same evening. The three frames look in three different directions and produce three different cities. The northern frame is full of the cathedral. The southern is full of the harbour. The eastern is mostly traffic. The fourth, west, was kept out by editorial agreement."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 04",
          "title": "First Hour, Middle, Last",
          "caption": "Three photographs from the same working day in the studio, taken at three points equidistant in time.",
          "folio": "p. 16",
          "body": "The studio is the same studio. The light, between the three frames, has done its slow work. The first-hour frame shows the room before the photographer has settled. The middle catches it mid-work, with a coffee cooling. The last-hour is the room beginning to be tidied, which is its preferred shape."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 05",
          "title": "Take One, Take Two, Take Three",
          "caption": "Three frames of the same set-up, made within twelve minutes, with adjustments to the available light only.",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "The set-up is the same set-up. The chair has not moved. The three exposures, made within twelve minutes of one another, differ only in the photographer's progressively diminishing patience with the light. By the third take, the room has been waiting longer than the photographer has, and the resulting frame is the most honest of the three."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 06",
          "title": "Plate I, Plate II, Plate III",
          "caption": "Opening triptych from a working portfolio, sequenced by exposure date, in chronological order.",
          "folio": "p. 24",
          "body": "The triptych is the opening sequence of a longer working portfolio. The three plates are arranged in the chronological order of their exposure. The exposures are nearly identical in technical specification. The differences between the three plates are, on close inspection, entirely a matter of weather and the photographer's patience, of which the second plate has appreciably less than the other two."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 07",
          "title": "Verse, Bridge, Chorus",
          "caption": "Three photographs that, in working sequence, behave with the structure of a song the photographer once heard.",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "The first photograph is the verse: it announces the subject, plainly, without raising its voice. The second photograph is the bridge: it complicates the subject, briefly, by turning it ninety degrees. The third photograph is the chorus: it returns to the subject as though the previous two frames had not happened, and is, in the project's working sequence, the one we keep coming back to."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 08",
          "title": "Setup, Crisis, Release",
          "caption": "Three frames in dramatic order, made over the course of forty-five minutes, in the same room.",
          "folio": "p. 32",
          "body": "The first frame is the setup: the table is laid, the chairs are arranged, the room is in its photogenic configuration. The second frame is the crisis: the dinner has not gone well, several plates are upturned, two of the four guests have left. The third frame is the release: the room is empty, the light has changed, and the table is in the shape it was always going to end up in."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 09",
          "title": "Plan, Action, Memory",
          "caption": "Three photographs from the same trip, sequenced not by date but by the photographer's relationship to the place.",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "The first frame is the plan: it is full of the optimism a photographer brings to a place not yet photographed. The second frame is the action: it is the working frame, made under conditions that did not entirely cooperate. The third frame is the memory: it was made on the morning of departure, and shows the place as the photographer would, eventually, remember it."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— SEQUENCE 10",
          "title": "Window, Door, Wall",
          "caption": "Three architectural details from the same Lisbon building, photographed on the same overcast afternoon.",
          "folio": "p. 40",
          "body": "The window is the most photographed of the three: it admits light, shows weather, frames a view. The door is the most ceremonious: it announces a boundary. The wall is the most patient of the three details, and is, in this triptych, the only one that has been there for longer than anyone the photographer met during the working visit."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
