      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 01 · WIDE",
          "title": "Across the Steppe",
          "caption": "Eastern Mongolia at first light.",
          "caption_2": "Working camp at four thousand metres.",
          "folio": "p. 06",
          "body": "The steppe is photographed badly, on average, because most photographers attempt to compress it. The view from the working camp at four thousand metres, on the third morning, was approximately three hundred and sixty degrees of horizon. We did not, on that morning, attempt to compress it. The frame on the left, by some margin the widest in the working portfolio, was the closest we came to admitting the scale of the country we had been crossing for six days, and is the picture this issue has been built around."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 02 · WIDE",
          "title": "The Slow Boat to Kerala",
          "caption": "Houseboat at Alleppey, dawn.",
          "caption_2": "Backwaters at midday, the working canal.",
          "folio": "p. 14",
          "body": "The Kerala backwaters move slowly, by design. The working houseboat made forty kilometres in three days, in conditions that would have been considered, by any sensible Western shipping inspector, profoundly inadequate. We did not file an inspection. The frames in this feature were made over the course of the third day. The photographer's morning frame, on the canal at dawn, is the most honest record we have of what slow travel actually feels like, by which we mean: it feels almost exactly like nothing at all."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 03 · WIDE",
          "title": "Salt Flats at Noon",
          "caption": "Salar de Uyuni, the working third day.",
          "caption_2": "Working vehicle, after the second flat.",
          "folio": "p. 22",
          "body": "The Bolivian salt flats are the largest mirror in the world for approximately three months a year, and an empty white plain for the other nine. We arrived at the wrong end of the wet season. The working third day was dry, hot, and almost entirely without features. The photographer made the wide frame here on the morning of that day, before the second flat tyre, and the picture is, in the editorial view, the strongest argument for visiting the working salt flats outside the busy reflection season."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 04 · WIDE",
          "title": "The Glacier in Retreat",
          "caption": "Working terminus, August.",
          "caption_2": "The same terminus, three years prior.",
          "folio": "p. 30",
          "body": "The wide photograph here was made at the working terminus of a particular Norwegian glacier, in August, by a contributor who has been visiting the same glacier for nine consecutive working summers. The terminus has, in those nine working years, retreated by approximately one hundred and forty metres. The smaller comparison frame, on the right, is from the same vantage three working years prior. The captions, by editorial choice, do not name the working glacier. The contributor has asked us to respect this, and we have."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 05 · WIDE",
          "title": "Walking the Wall",
          "caption": "Hadrian's Wall, Birdoswald section.",
          "caption_2": "Working bivouac, second night.",
          "folio": "p. 38",
          "body": "Hadrian's Wall is a long and not particularly comfortable walk in the working autumn, especially if the weather has decided to be honest about it. The wide frame here was made on the third afternoon, near the Birdoswald section, in conditions that would have been considered, by any working hiker who knew better, sufficient cause for an early departure. The photographer kept walking. The bivouac frame on the right, made the next morning, is the more accurate document of what the working walk actually involved."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 06 · WIDE",
          "title": "Two Lakes and a Volcano",
          "caption": "Working lake, north of Pucón.",
          "caption_2": "Working summit, first attempt, abandoned.",
          "folio": "p. 46",
          "body": "The wide frame here was made on the working third day at a particular lake north of Pucón, on the morning the volcano above it was, briefly, visible through the customary cloud. The photographer had been at the lake for two days waiting for this, and chose, after making the wide frame, to attempt the summit by way of the northern face. The summit attempt is documented in the smaller frame on the right, and was, in the working note, abandoned within four hours of the start of the working ascent."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 07 · WIDE",
          "title": "The Open Pacific",
          "caption": "Working day eight, four thousand kilometres from land.",
          "caption_2": "Working bridge, the night watch.",
          "folio": "p. 54",
          "body": "The Pacific is photographed badly, on average, by anyone who has not spent at least a week on it. The contributor for this feature spent fifteen working days on a small research vessel between Auckland and Valparaíso. The wide frame here was made on the working day eight, in conditions that the working captain described as average for the latitude. The night-watch frame on the right, made by the working second officer, was given to the contributor on the morning of the working departure from the harbour."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 08 · WIDE",
          "title": "Across the Pyrenees",
          "caption": "Working ridge, the high pass.",
          "caption_2": "Working hut, the second evening.",
          "folio": "p. 62",
          "body": "The high passes of the working central Pyrenees are, in October, the kind of working country that does not flatter the working photographer. The wide frame here was made on the working third afternoon, near the high pass at the Spanish-French border, in conditions that the working hut keeper described as adequate. The hut frame on the right, made the previous evening, is the most honest record we have of what the working pass actually felt like to spend a working evening at, in working autumn weather."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 09 · WIDE",
          "title": "The Long Estuary",
          "caption": "Working estuary at low tide, day three.",
          "caption_2": "Working harbour, the corresponding evening.",
          "folio": "p. 70",
          "body": "The long working estuary photographed in this feature is on the working west coast of Ireland, and is photographed badly, on average, because it is too wide for most working frames. The wide picture here, made on the working third day at low tide, is the closest the contributor has come to admitting the scale of the working bay. The harbour frame on the right, made the same evening at the working town pier, is included for working scale, and demonstrates the working size of the boats the working bay can accommodate."
        },
        {
          "eyebrow": "— FEATURE 10 · WIDE",
          "title": "Where the Steppe Ends",
          "caption": "Working southern edge of the working steppe.",
          "caption_2": "Working camel station, the corresponding morning.",
          "folio": "p. 78",
          "body": "The working southern edge of the working Mongolian steppe is, in the working photographer's account, the most photographable part of the country, on the working condition that the photographer has the patience to wait for the working light. The wide frame here was made on the working sixth day, in conditions the working guide described as the third-best of the working visit. The camel station on the right, photographed the corresponding morning, is the working station from which the working fortnight's expedition departed."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
    },
