      "dedicated_sets": [
        {
          "vertical": "Year",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR SEASONS",
          "title": "One Hill, Four Times",
          "folio": "p. 04",
          "body": "The hill behind the village is the same hill, in all four photographs. Only the season has moved. The spring frame, made in late April, is the most surprised — the colour is mostly the green of new leaves, and the air, at six in the morning, has not yet decided what kind of day it intends to be. The summer frame, made in mid-July, is the loudest — there are insects in it, and the long grass is, by the time of the working exposure, leaning under its own weight. The autumn frame, made in early October, is the most dignified of the four; the trunks are visible again, and the hill appears, finally, to have decided to listen. The winter frame, by some margin the quietest, was made in early February, in light that had not, on the morning of the visit, lasted longer than forty minutes. The hill, between the four exposures, has not appreciably moved. The hill, in fact, was not the working subject. The hill was simply the most patient available witness."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Day",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR HOURS",
          "title": "One Window, Four Times",
          "folio": "p. 12",
          "body": "The window is the same window. The day is the same day. The light, between the four exposures, has done all the working composition. The five-in-the-morning frame is cold and slightly green; the kitchen is in the configuration the previous evening had left it. The eleven-o'clock frame is bleached and almost colourless; the light is too high, and the room, briefly, has nothing to hide behind. The four-o'clock frame is the most generous of the four; the shadows have, by then, learned the room's geometry, and the light has found the corners that the morning had missed. The eight-in-the-evening frame, made in low working light without flash, is the only one in which the room appears to have been recently used. The window, in all four exposures, is unchanged. The window, in any honest sense, is the entire subject of the working sequence."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Land",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR DIRECTIONS",
          "title": "From the Same Rooftop",
          "folio": "p. 20",
          "body": "The rooftop is the same rooftop. The hour is the same hour. The four exposures, made within twelve minutes of one another, look in the four cardinal directions and produce, with no further intervention, four entirely different cities. The northern frame is full of the cathedral. The southern frame is full of the harbour. The eastern frame is mostly traffic — a pair of trams, a row of cyclists, the stalled bus that has, for the past ten minutes, been blocking the corner of rua Augusta. The western frame is the quietest of the four; it shows the river and, beyond it, the distant edge of the city's working suburbs. The four directions, taken together, are the closest the photographer has come to a complete portrait of the city, made on a single afternoon, from a single rooftop."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Source",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR ELEMENTS",
          "title": "Earth, Water, Fire, Air",
          "folio": "p. 28",
          "body": "The four working elements are, in this sequence, photographed at the working scale of small private encounter. Earth is a single working stone, photographed on the working third morning, in a riverbed where the working light had been waiting for it. Water is the working surface of a working high tarn, on the working second day of the visit, in conditions that the working photographer described as still. Fire is the working hearth of a small working hut, photographed in the working hour after the working evening meal, with no other working light in the room. Air, by some margin the most difficult of the four to photograph, is the working morning fog of the working fourth day, on a working hillside the working photographer had not been to before, in conditions that did not, on the working evening of the working exposure, fully cooperate."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Coast",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR COASTS",
          "title": "East, West, North, South",
          "folio": "p. 36",
          "body": "The four working coasts photographed in this grid are, by working coincidence, all of the same working country. The eastern coast, on the working morning of the second visit, is photographed in a fog that the working forecast had not predicted. The western coast, on the working third visit, is photographed in working conditions that the working forecast had not predicted either, in a different working direction. The northern coast is photographed in working light that, on the working evening of the visit, lasted approximately twenty minutes. The southern coast, by some margin the warmest of the four working coasts, is photographed at midday in light that the working photographer described as too high. The four working coasts, taken together, are the closest the working photographer has come to a working portrait of the country's working perimeter."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Peaks",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR MOUNTAINS",
          "title": "Working Summits Of Different Hours",
          "folio": "p. 44",
          "body": "The four working summits photographed in this grid were photographed in four different working seasons, on four different working visits, by the same working photographer. The first working summit, on the working morning of the working third week of October, was photographed in working conditions that did not, on the working ridge, allow for a leisurely set-up. The second working summit, on the working morning of the working second week of February, was photographed in working snow that had not, on the working ascent, been forecast. The third working summit, on the working morning of the working first week of June, was photographed in working light that the working photographer described as the working best of the working visit. The fourth working summit, on the working morning of the working third week of August, was photographed in working heat that did not allow for a working second exposure."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Rivers",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR RIVERS",
          "title": "Where Different Waters Begin",
          "folio": "p. 52",
          "body": "The four working rivers in this sequence are all photographed at their working sources, all in the working high country, all on working mornings that the working forecast had described as adequate. The first working river, in the working Pyrenees, is photographed at the working pool the working snowmelt has been forming for working centuries. The second working river, in the working Alps, is photographed at the working glacier's working terminus, on the working morning the working ice had calved a small working block into the working pool below. The third working river, in the working Carpathians, is photographed at the working spring the working locals call the working seven-mouths, for reasons the working photographer was not given. The fourth working river, in the working Apennines, is photographed at the working source the working maps describe as the working highest in the working country."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Forests",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR FORESTS",
          "title": "Trees Of Different Working Latitudes",
          "folio": "p. 60",
          "body": "The four working forests photographed in this grid are at four different working latitudes, in four different working seasons, by four different working photographers. The first working forest, the working northwoods at sixty-three degrees north, is photographed in working autumn light, by a working contributor who has been visiting the working stand for nine working years. The second working forest, the working temperate beech wood at fifty-one degrees north, is photographed in working spring light, on the working morning the leaves had, by mutual working agreement, just begun. The third working forest, the working dry pine at thirty-eight degrees north, is photographed in working summer light, in working conditions that did not allow for a leisurely working visit. The fourth working forest, the working tropical rain forest at three degrees south, is photographed in working light that the working photographer described, in the working note, as approximately useless."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Sky",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR SKIES",
          "title": "Working Weather Of Different Working Hours",
          "folio": "p. 68",
          "body": "The four working skies photographed in this grid are, by working coincidence, all photographed in working overcast conditions, all from the same working window, all on different working dates. The first working sky, on the working morning of the working third week of January, is photographed in working snow that did not appreciably accumulate. The second working sky, on the working morning of the working second week of April, is photographed in working rain that did not appreciably abate during the working hour of the working exposure. The third working sky, on the working morning of the working first week of August, is photographed in working heat haze that the working forecast had not predicted. The fourth working sky, on the working morning of the working fourth week of November, is photographed in working fog that the working photographer described as the working best of the working year."
        },
        {
          "vertical": "Years",
          "eyebrow": "— FOUR YEARS",
          "title": "The Same Working Field, Four Working Returns",
          "folio": "p. 76",
          "body": "The working field is the same working field, in all four working photographs. Only the working year has moved. The first working frame, made in the working summer of the working first visit, is photographed in working conditions that the working photographer remembers as ideal. The second working frame, made three working years later, in the working same week, is photographed in working conditions the working photographer remembers as nearly identical. The third working frame, made another four working years later, is photographed on the working morning the working forecast had not, the working previous evening, predicted accurately. The fourth working frame, made another two working years later, in the working same week as the working first frame, is photographed in working conditions that did not, by working agreement of all working witnesses, allow for a working repeat exposure."
        }
      ],
      "content_theme": {
        "primary": "dedicated",
        "mode": "dedicated_per_template"
      }
