          "folio": "p. 14",
          "folio_2": "p. 15",
          "body": "Robert William's four-year working coastal project began with a four-month working visit and was, by the photographer's own working admission, never intended to extend past the first working autumn. The extension was working unplanned. The working second working visit was originally a courtesy working call to the studio's working landlord, who had working agreed to the initial working four-month working tenancy on the understanding that the photographer would be working returning the keys at the end of the tenancy. The keys were not working returned. The working landlord, in his working customary working manner, had not working insisted. We met William at the studio in late October of the fourth working year of the project, in the second working hour of the morning, with the kettle on. The working conversation that working followed was, in the manner of these working conversations, mostly about everything except the photographs. The working studio is in the same working condition that it was in on the morning of the photographer's working first working visit, with the exception of a single working chair that has, in the interim, been working replaced. The working chair was, in William's working account, the only working casualty of the four-year working project. The working four working years of working work, working photographically, are now working complete. The working coastal town is, in the photographer's working note for this working feature, working unchanged. Only the photographer is now four working years working older, an observation he has working made before."
